00:09:56.764 --> 00:09:59.224
So we're going to move straight into science.

152
00:10:00.264 --> 00:10:03.134
And I'm starting with this slide that I

153
00:10:03.164 --> 00:10:06.874
showed in 2002 at the New Orleans meeting when

154
00:10:07.204 --> 00:10:10.984
I gave an education session. And the point of this slide is to

155
00:10:12.964 --> 00:10:16.944
describe a phenomenon that I've seen over the last 25 years, sort of

156
00:10:16.984 --> 00:10:19.964
being in the front row of the development of many targeted agents.

157
00:10:20.434 --> 00:10:20.974
And that is,

158
00:10:21.804 --> 00:10:25.304
if we understand the biology of the tumor and know what the driver is, and have the

159
00:10:26.224 --> 00:10:30.104
fortune to have a pharmacological strategy to inhibit, we get great

160
00:10:30.164 --> 00:10:30.844
responses.

161
00:10:31.824 --> 00:10:32.044
But we

162
00:10:34.024 --> 00:10:36.444
realize that there's the problem of acquired resistance.

163
00:10:37.264 --> 00:10:41.034
And in the first many years of developing these

164
00:10:41.064 --> 00:10:44.264
different targeted therapies, the resistance

165
00:10:44.304 --> 00:10:47.704
mechanisms were worked out one by one, and they are

166
00:10:47.724 --> 00:10:51.024
mutations, amplifications, bypass pathways, et cetera.

167
00:10:52.264 --> 00:10:54.084
But as that then informed

168
00:10:55.684 --> 00:10:59.644
more intelligent ways of coming up with next gen therapies, we started to

169
00:10:59.684 --> 00:11:03.204
see a change to different mechanisms of resistance, which we call

170
00:11:03.264 --> 00:11:06.884
off-target. And I've summarized this here, again, from the

171
00:11:06.944 --> 00:11:10.724
closing slide from four years ago, that I felt that

172
00:11:10.784 --> 00:11:13.744
we sort of learned the rules for on-target resistance.

173
00:11:13.984 --> 00:11:17.404
We know how to make better inhibitors, but as we put more and more selective

174
00:11:17.504 --> 00:11:20.364
pressure on that initial driver, we start seeing new escape

175
00:11:20.444 --> 00:11:24.404
mechanisms. And this is something that is now a new challenge, and

176
00:11:24.524 --> 00:11:28.204
I concluded with the statement that we should be able to beat

177
00:11:28.304 --> 00:11:32.084
lineage plasticity if we can understand the molecular underpinnings.

178
00:11:32.124 --> 00:11:35.924
So my task today is to report back to you, four years later, on what we've learned.

179
00:11:36.644 --> 00:11:40.484
And the disease that I'm going to discuss this in is in prostate cancer.

180
00:11:41.264 --> 00:11:44.584
But I think our findings are quite relevant to other

181
00:11:44.644 --> 00:11:45.764
epithelial tumors.

182
00:11:46.944 --> 00:11:50.224
So when I first started working deeply in prostate cancer,

183
00:11:51.404 --> 00:11:55.104
the question was: What is the cause of acquired resistance to first generation

184
00:11:55.204 --> 00:11:59.144
hormone therapy? These are drugs that lower systemic androgen levels

185
00:11:59.204 --> 00:12:02.984
as well as antagonists that competitively inhibit binding of

186
00:12:03.024 --> 00:12:04.964
testosterone to the androgen receptor.

187
00:12:05.494 --> 00:12:09.444
And what we and others found over a series of years is something

188
00:12:09.504 --> 00:12:13.434
that now, in the light of what I just showed you, was probably sort

189
00:12:13.444 --> 00:12:17.232
of staring us in the face, and that is, it's the target.And

190
00:12:17.292 --> 00:12:21.252
its changes in androgen receptor expression levels through amplification,

191
00:12:21.432 --> 00:12:23.252
splice variants, mutations, etc.

192
00:12:24.652 --> 00:12:28.352
That work or that finding in my case sparked a collaboration with Dr.

193
00:12:28.592 --> 00:12:32.192
Michael Jung to develop a next generation anti-androgen.

194
00:12:32.712 --> 00:12:36.682
And what came out of that work is a drug called enzalutamide that's now been on

195
00:12:36.712 --> 00:12:38.432
the market since 2012

196
00:12:39.872 --> 00:12:43.852
and has proven to be quite effective in men with castration-resistant prostate

197
00:12:43.912 --> 00:12:47.892
cancer. I had no role in the clinical development of the drug, but I was very

198
00:12:47.932 --> 00:12:51.852
pleased to open up an issue of New England Journal a couple of years ago

199
00:12:51.892 --> 00:12:55.841
to see this randomized Phase III trial in men who are early

200
00:12:55.872 --> 00:12:59.582
in prostate cancer relapse. They have what's called biochemical relapse.

201
00:13:00.082 --> 00:13:03.812
And you can see from the Kaplan-Meier curve that there's quite a significant

202
00:13:03.932 --> 00:13:07.792
survival advantage in men who receive the androgen-lowering drug plus

203
00:13:07.832 --> 00:13:10.292
enzalutamide. So men are living longer,

204
00:13:11.272 --> 00:13:13.731
tens of thousands of men benefiting around the world.

205
00:13:14.692 --> 00:13:14.792
But

206
00:13:15.692 --> 00:13:19.372
it's still not a cure, so what's the next challenge?

207
00:13:20.092 --> 00:13:23.822
So I go back to this cartoon and now show you that this

208
00:13:23.872 --> 00:13:27.622
simple diagram of where adenocarcinoma would progress through increased

209
00:13:27.732 --> 00:13:30.872
androgen receptor activity to a resistant

210
00:13:30.912 --> 00:13:34.452
adenocarcinoma. We're starting to see new

211
00:13:34.512 --> 00:13:37.932
patterns of resistance where the histology of the tumor in its most

212
00:13:37.972 --> 00:13:41.572
extreme form can undergo a complete lineage switch from an

213
00:13:41.632 --> 00:13:45.622
adenocarcinoma to a neuroendocrine cancer that looks for all

214
00:13:45.632 --> 00:13:47.372
the world like small cell lung cancer.

215
00:13:47.672 --> 00:13:51.552
And indeed, the transcription factors that these tumors express are

216
00:13:51.592 --> 00:13:55.452
sort of a dead match for those that are seen in different subtypes of small

217
00:13:55.532 --> 00:13:59.372
cell lung cancer. So for the rest of the talk, I'm going to tell you how

218
00:13:59.452 --> 00:14:03.412
we've tried to understand how this process happens, with the idea

219
00:14:03.492 --> 00:14:03.952
that if we can

220
00:14:04.912 --> 00:14:08.552
do that, maybe we can get a toehold into how to stop this or prevent

221
00:14:08.612 --> 00:14:12.452
it. And in order to tackle this question scientifically, it

222
00:14:12.512 --> 00:14:16.412
was critical to have models in the laboratory in which we could

223
00:14:16.592 --> 00:14:18.152
watch the transition occur

224
00:14:18.972 --> 00:14:22.652
in a reasonable period of time and then have the ability to perturb that

225
00:14:22.692 --> 00:14:25.052
system to identify vulnerabilities.

226
00:14:26.572 --> 00:14:30.552
So the first success in that came from taking advantage

227
00:14:30.592 --> 00:14:32.412
of the tumor suppressor genes

228
00:14:33.292 --> 00:14:35.232
that are mutated in these different states.

229
00:14:36.172 --> 00:14:39.462
What we know from tumor genome sequencing is that PTEN and

230
00:14:39.532 --> 00:14:43.472
p53 loss of function mutations are seen in about 50% of

231
00:14:43.532 --> 00:14:47.172
men with castration-resistant prostate cancer, but they tend to segregate

232
00:14:47.182 --> 00:14:49.572
across all of these different subtypes.

233
00:14:49.612 --> 00:14:53.452
Whereas loss of RB, the RB tumor suppressor gene

234
00:14:53.492 --> 00:14:57.412
is found in about 20 or 30% of cases and it seems to

235
00:14:57.472 --> 00:15:00.752
be tightly correlated with the appearance of this neuroendocrine

236
00:15:00.812 --> 00:15:01.511
histology.

237
00:15:02.432 --> 00:15:06.142
So taking advantage of those tumor suppressor gene insights,

238
00:15:06.652 --> 00:15:09.252
David Goodrich from Roswell Park

239
00:15:10.292 --> 00:15:14.192
crossed mice with floxed alleles of these different tumor suppressors in

240
00:15:14.232 --> 00:15:17.292
various combinations and then did a prostate-specific deletion.

241
00:15:17.821 --> 00:15:21.752
And what he found is that when he deleted RB in combination with either of

242
00:15:21.792 --> 00:15:24.832
the other two suppressors or all three together, he got an

243
00:15:24.912 --> 00:15:27.772
adenocarcinoma that transitioned to a neuroendocrine cancer.

244
00:15:28.372 --> 00:15:32.272
We teamed up with David to do single-cell RNA sequencing of a time course

245
00:15:32.312 --> 00:15:35.912
of these mice. And what we saw on the right was the

246
00:15:35.952 --> 00:15:39.552
appearance of the adenocarcinoma cells. All the tumor cells are marked in red.

247
00:15:40.572 --> 00:15:44.232
And then subsequently, the emergence of the neuroendocrine tumor that we had seen

248
00:15:44.272 --> 00:15:47.992
histologically. But what we also saw were the appearance of other

249
00:15:48.032 --> 00:15:51.912
subpopulations that are clearly different lineages that

250
00:15:51.952 --> 00:15:55.272
had been missed histologically, but clearly appear in the mice.

251
00:15:55.612 --> 00:15:58.892
This one is of some interest. It's defined by a transcription factor known as

252
00:15:58.932 --> 00:16:02.912
POW2F3 that remarkably defines a subset of small cell lung

253
00:16:02.952 --> 00:16:06.612
cancer well-recognized, as well as mesenchymal tumors.

254
00:16:06.652 --> 00:16:10.592
But those of you who do mouse genetics will know that if you just look at

255
00:16:10.652 --> 00:16:11.032
this

256
00:16:12.312 --> 00:16:13.882
triple cross mouse, this is

257
00:16:14.952 --> 00:16:18.652
a total of seven alleles to generate one experiment, and additional

258
00:16:18.692 --> 00:16:22.332
perturbations would require not only money, time, mouse

259
00:16:22.392 --> 00:16:25.472
cages, etc. We needed a new system to move more quickly.

260
00:16:26.412 --> 00:16:29.632
So Rodrigo Romero in my lab developed that system.

261
00:16:30.632 --> 00:16:34.582
What he did was to take advantage of our expertise in

262
00:16:34.912 --> 00:16:38.852
isolating normal prostate tissue from a mouse and being able to grow it in culture

263
00:16:38.892 --> 00:16:42.132
and retain all the cell types that are present in vivo.

264
00:16:42.492 --> 00:16:46.092
And then he developed very efficient ways of genomically

265
00:16:46.102 --> 00:16:49.452
perturbing them using CRISPR as well as lentiviral

266
00:16:49.492 --> 00:16:52.862
infections to create, if you will, a sort of genetic menu of

267
00:16:53.232 --> 00:16:56.412
choice. When he combined RB and

268
00:16:56.692 --> 00:16:59.732
p53 and overexpression of MYC, another

269
00:16:59.972 --> 00:17:03.892
common finding in advanced prostate cancer, he

270
00:17:03.932 --> 00:17:07.172
got a beautiful model that replicated what we had seen in the genetically

271
00:17:07.232 --> 00:17:11.072
engineered mice, and that is an adenocarcinoma that transitions to a

272
00:17:11.093 --> 00:17:14.312
neuroendocrine cancer with lymph node metastases and lung

273
00:17:14.353 --> 00:17:18.333
metastases. And this is now in a matter of weeks instead of years.

274
00:17:19.873 --> 00:17:23.562
So the next question is what are the sort of triggers that

275
00:17:23.652 --> 00:17:24.952
cause this transition?

276
00:17:26.142 --> 00:17:29.502
And I should mention in order to see this transition,

277
00:17:30.472 --> 00:17:32.552
Rodrigo had to put the cells into the mouse.

278
00:17:32.592 --> 00:17:35.692
If he maintained them in organoid culture, they would stay in the

279
00:17:35.732 --> 00:17:37.992
adenocarcinoma fate. So

280
00:17:39.172 --> 00:17:42.792
what Teng Han in the lab noticed is that there's a rich

281
00:17:43.032 --> 00:17:46.492
stromal proliferation, a CAF population that appears when the

282
00:17:46.592 --> 00:17:49.832
adenocarcinoma is growing in its early stages.

283
00:17:50.172 --> 00:17:53.952
But then when it transitions to the neuroendocrine state, you see this

284
00:17:54.012 --> 00:17:56.072
relative depletion of the fibroblasts.

285
00:17:57.372 --> 00:18:00.982
So since fibroblasts make extracellular matrix and

286
00:18:01.032 --> 00:18:01.452
since

287
00:18:02.352 --> 00:18:05.692
extracellular matrix is a key ingredient in our

288
00:18:05.912 --> 00:18:09.412
organoid culture, Teng had the idea of perhaps

289
00:18:10.552 --> 00:18:14.532
the transition is not occurring in vitro because we've got too much

290
00:18:14.592 --> 00:18:18.516
matrix as in this stateSo to cut to the chase,

291
00:18:18.636 --> 00:18:22.426
he did a very simple experiment, which is to take the organoids out of Matrigel and

292
00:18:22.476 --> 00:18:23.976
grow them in suspension culture.

293
00:18:24.896 --> 00:18:26.396
And it was quite dramatic that

294
00:18:27.716 --> 00:18:31.336
at seven days, he could see a blush of expression of the neuroendocrine

295
00:18:31.436 --> 00:18:31.816
lineage

296
00:18:32.676 --> 00:18:36.596
master regulator ASCL1, which went to much higher levels after two

297
00:18:36.696 --> 00:18:40.376
weeks and stayed that way in continuous culture.

298
00:18:40.396 --> 00:18:42.416
And you can see this at the protein level as well.

299
00:18:42.496 --> 00:18:46.276
You can see ASCL1 positive cells in these organoids that

300
00:18:46.796 --> 00:18:49.496
have a morphologic appearance of adenocarcinoma.

301
00:18:50.336 --> 00:18:54.256
If you keep passaging these organoids, the rest of the organoid doesn't fill

302
00:18:54.336 --> 00:18:58.116
in, so it's this spotty mosaic pattern, which I'll come back to in just a minute.

303
00:18:59.816 --> 00:19:02.976
So putting cells in suspension is a pretty dramatic

304
00:19:04.456 --> 00:19:08.046
stress to put them under. So to get more focused on whether it was

305
00:19:08.136 --> 00:19:11.756
truly extracellular matrix that was the driver of this

306
00:19:12.036 --> 00:19:14.696
change, we looked at integrin signaling.

307
00:19:14.756 --> 00:19:18.566
So the two main ingredients in Matrigel are collagen and laminin, and

308
00:19:18.596 --> 00:19:22.516
they both work through engagement of the integrin receptor, and they share

309
00:19:22.636 --> 00:19:26.616
a common subunit known as beta-1. So what's shown

310
00:19:26.656 --> 00:19:30.366
here on the far right is in organoids grown in

311
00:19:30.396 --> 00:19:34.356
Matrigel, if you delete the ability of the organoids to

312
00:19:34.396 --> 00:19:38.296
recognize the extracellular matrix by deleting the beta-1's common

313
00:19:38.336 --> 00:19:42.106
subunit, you can reproduce what he had seen in suspension culture, which is this

314
00:19:42.156 --> 00:19:45.906
ASCL1 sort of pattern of expression in this

315
00:19:45.996 --> 00:19:46.836
mosaic pattern.

316
00:19:48.336 --> 00:19:51.416
So the next question is: What's downstream?

317
00:19:51.816 --> 00:19:55.056
So what I've shown you so far is extracellular matrix engages the

318
00:19:55.076 --> 00:19:58.776
receptor and is exerting a break or a restraint on the

319
00:19:58.816 --> 00:20:02.456
ability of these RB-deleted cells that want to undergo the lineage

320
00:20:02.496 --> 00:20:06.476
transition, but they're being prevented. So what is it that's doing the preventing?

321
00:20:07.356 --> 00:20:11.116
So you can look at signaling diagrams of integrin engagement

322
00:20:11.196 --> 00:20:13.616
downstream, and there are many pathways.

323
00:20:13.696 --> 00:20:16.176
I think a lot of you are familiar with these.

324
00:20:16.836 --> 00:20:20.016
We looked one by one to try to figure out who's the culprit.

325
00:20:20.046 --> 00:20:23.936
And the culprit turns out to be the pathway involving YAP, TAZ,

326
00:20:24.276 --> 00:20:26.476
and the DNA-binding protein TEAD.

327
00:20:27.236 --> 00:20:31.116
And the way we got there was to take advantage of a

328
00:20:31.196 --> 00:20:33.996
small molecule inhibitor of a kinase known as

329
00:20:34.056 --> 00:20:37.836
LATS-1/2 that had been developed by

330
00:20:38.456 --> 00:20:41.636
Jim Hudspeth's lab across the street at Rockefeller University.

331
00:20:43.156 --> 00:20:46.636
So this pathway between integrin engagement and YAP,

332
00:20:47.376 --> 00:20:48.536
TAZ, and TEAD

333
00:20:49.516 --> 00:20:52.956
is very interesting and well studied in Hippo

334
00:20:53.056 --> 00:20:53.556
signaling.

335
00:20:54.576 --> 00:20:57.976
It's important to realize that it's a series of negative steps.

336
00:20:58.496 --> 00:21:02.056
So in this case, giving the LATS inhibitor blocks the kinase

337
00:21:02.136 --> 00:21:05.756
activity and prevents YAP from being phosphorylated.

338
00:21:06.066 --> 00:21:08.936
An unphosphorylated YAP is the active form.

339
00:21:09.656 --> 00:21:13.176
So to test out whether this tool compound would be useful in our

340
00:21:13.256 --> 00:21:17.156
system, we did this experiment over here where we put the cells in suspension.

341
00:21:17.776 --> 00:21:21.676
They will start to express ASCL1

342
00:21:21.736 --> 00:21:22.676
if we wait long enough,

343
00:21:23.656 --> 00:21:26.596
and we see the loss of

344
00:21:27.676 --> 00:21:31.446
YAP activity because we see loss of expression of a YAP target gene here,

345
00:21:32.176 --> 00:21:35.636
and we see the phosphorylation of YAP by LATS kinase, which

346
00:21:35.696 --> 00:21:39.036
is now on because this negative signal is released,

347
00:21:40.156 --> 00:21:42.236
and we can reverse that with the LATS inhibitor.

348
00:21:42.536 --> 00:21:46.456
But the key experiment was to keep them in suspension long enough for them to

349
00:21:46.556 --> 00:21:50.426
start to go into the neuroendocrine state, so they're expressing lots of ASCL1,

350
00:21:50.816 --> 00:21:54.496
and then add the LATS inhibitor. And what you can see here is we can reverse

351
00:21:54.556 --> 00:21:58.406
that upregulation of ASCL1. So this tells us that

352
00:21:58.456 --> 00:22:02.216
this lineage transition, once it starts to happen, is potentially

353
00:22:02.256 --> 00:22:05.036
reversible pharmacologically, and I'll come back to that.

354
00:22:06.716 --> 00:22:08.796
So here's what the cartoon now looks like.

355
00:22:08.856 --> 00:22:12.456
In the adenocarcinoma state, when there's plenty of extracellular matrix and

356
00:22:12.476 --> 00:22:16.296
stroma, you've got cells that are poised because of RB loss to

357
00:22:16.316 --> 00:22:19.196
undergo the transition, but this is a brake on that system.

358
00:22:19.816 --> 00:22:23.416
But if you remove the matrix, you block the integrin signaling, and as I'll show

359
00:22:23.476 --> 00:22:26.796
you on the next slide, if you interfere specifically with just the

360
00:22:26.876 --> 00:22:30.416
YAP/TEAD interface binding with a small

361
00:22:30.476 --> 00:22:34.156
molecule protein interaction disruptor that's been

362
00:22:34.176 --> 00:22:35.435
developed by Novartis,

363
00:22:36.336 --> 00:22:40.036
you can push these cells all the way to this other state, a neuroendocrine

364
00:22:40.136 --> 00:22:43.896
state that turns on. So here's an example of the TEAD inhibitor.

365
00:22:43.936 --> 00:22:46.736
So here's, again, a series of organoids grown in

366
00:22:47.716 --> 00:22:49.756
standard media where there's no ASCL1.

367
00:22:50.216 --> 00:22:53.856
The TEAD drug does just what I showed you with suspension and integrin receptor

368
00:22:53.896 --> 00:22:57.556
knockout. You see the activation of ASCL1 in a subset of the

369
00:22:57.596 --> 00:23:01.356
cells. And now we've layered on a second pathway, and this is the Notch

370
00:23:01.476 --> 00:23:05.296
pathway, and this inhibition is done using a gamma

371
00:23:05.336 --> 00:23:09.116
secretase inhibitor. And you can see that a subset of cells will also

372
00:23:09.176 --> 00:23:09.356
turn

373
00:23:11.216 --> 00:23:13.436
ASCL1 positive with Notch inhibition.

374
00:23:13.746 --> 00:23:17.176
And we did this experiment because Notch is implicated in small cell lung cancer

375
00:23:17.256 --> 00:23:21.086
transitions. And David Goodrich, who I mentioned earlier, also has some evidence

376
00:23:21.086 --> 00:23:23.276
that it's involved in this transition.

377
00:23:23.296 --> 00:23:26.636
But what I think is really striking is on the far right, and that is when we

378
00:23:26.696 --> 00:23:30.276
combine these two, we solve that problem that I mentioned earlier.

379
00:23:30.336 --> 00:23:34.306
That mosaic pattern now disappears, and we are getting essentially 100% of

380
00:23:34.336 --> 00:23:38.066
the cells turning to ASCL1 positive.

381
00:23:38.576 --> 00:23:42.516
So this now gave us an opportunity to really ask if we

382
00:23:42.556 --> 00:23:45.496
could develop, sort of recreate the entire

383
00:23:45.916 --> 00:23:49.896
adeno to neuroendocrine transition in an organoid cultured in

384
00:23:49.976 --> 00:23:50.876
vitro system.

385
00:23:52.316 --> 00:23:55.596
And in order to ask the next question, we did the following experiment.

386
00:23:55.676 --> 00:23:59.076
So we used the YAP/TEAD inhibitor, we used the Notch

387
00:23:59.216 --> 00:24:03.036
inhibitor, the gamma secretase, and we used enzalutamide to inhibit

388
00:24:03.156 --> 00:24:06.856
all three pathways at once in cells in organoid culture, and then

389
00:24:06.916 --> 00:24:08.456
harvest cells at different times,

390
00:24:09.876 --> 00:24:13.856
after eight days or after 42 days. And we did this as singlets,

391
00:24:13.996 --> 00:24:16.296
doublets, and triple drug therapy.

392
00:24:17.236 --> 00:24:21.126
And we then harvested the cells and performed bulk RNA sequencing and

393
00:24:21.196 --> 00:24:25.096
plotted the data on a principal component analysis. And I'll orient you.

394
00:24:25.416 --> 00:24:28.336
The cells that have no treatment are in DMSO.

395
00:24:28.596 --> 00:24:32.256
Their transcriptome maps on this plot down to the bottom left.

396
00:24:32.296 --> 00:24:35.856
And as a positive control for the neuroendocrine state, we

397
00:24:35.916 --> 00:24:39.906
isolated tumors from mice that had undergone the full neuroendocrine transition,

398
00:24:40.316 --> 00:24:44.060
and that's this cluster of... tumors over

399
00:24:44.120 --> 00:24:46.260
here. And what I hope you can see is that

400
00:24:47.460 --> 00:24:51.400
four to six weeks of continuous treatment with these drugs

401
00:24:51.860 --> 00:24:55.480
is able to move the cells all the way to the fully neuroendocrine

402
00:24:55.600 --> 00:24:59.480
state. We can also confirm that at the protein level by doing

403
00:24:59.520 --> 00:25:03.280
western blots of these in vitro differentiated cells versus the

404
00:25:03.360 --> 00:25:07.340
actual tumors. And you can see we get expression of many of the canonical

405
00:25:07.380 --> 00:25:11.360
neuroendocrine markers, showing that we've faithfully replicated

406
00:25:11.400 --> 00:25:15.300
the system. So now that we have this system, we can start to take apart

407
00:25:15.360 --> 00:25:19.300
the molecular details of what's happening during these early time points

408
00:25:19.360 --> 00:25:21.700
that sets this process underway.

409
00:25:23.120 --> 00:25:26.580
And one of the first experiments we did was to look at the

410
00:25:29.000 --> 00:25:32.700
chromatin binding sites of both YAP and TEAD at the

411
00:25:32.720 --> 00:25:36.610
beginning and at the end. And what you can see is

412
00:25:36.660 --> 00:25:40.460
in the adenocarcinoma state, you see these set of TEAD

413
00:25:40.500 --> 00:25:44.370
binding peaks that overlap very nicely with the YAP binding

414
00:25:44.420 --> 00:25:47.280
peaks, as you would expect, because this is a two protein

415
00:25:48.020 --> 00:25:49.710
heterodimer transcription factor.

416
00:25:50.320 --> 00:25:53.140
And you can see the appearance of the enrichment for TEAD

417
00:25:53.840 --> 00:25:57.000
motifs. But what caught us by complete surprise

418
00:25:57.860 --> 00:26:01.020
is that we see a whole new set of TEAD binding peaks at different

419
00:26:01.080 --> 00:26:04.860
loci in the neuroendocrine state when there's no YAP

420
00:26:05.400 --> 00:26:06.320
and no TAZ.

421
00:26:07.220 --> 00:26:11.120
And this confirms that indeed these are TEAD motifs where

422
00:26:11.160 --> 00:26:13.320
these peaks are binding. And interestingly,

423
00:26:14.140 --> 00:26:17.800
closely associated motif with these new peaks is the

424
00:26:19.180 --> 00:26:22.800
consensus motif for FOXA1, a well-known pioneer

425
00:26:22.900 --> 00:26:26.140
transcription factor, which is expressed in the adenocarcinoma state.

426
00:26:27.160 --> 00:26:31.020
So we then asked what's happening to FOXA1, and FOXA1

427
00:26:31.060 --> 00:26:35.000
is present in the adenocarcinoma state at these peaks and relocalizes

428
00:26:36.240 --> 00:26:38.700
at the same sites as the TEAD binding

429
00:26:38.800 --> 00:26:42.000
peaks in the neuroendocrine state.

430
00:26:43.480 --> 00:26:47.370
And so what we now know is that if we delete FOXA1 in this system, we can

431
00:26:47.400 --> 00:26:51.080
prevent the transition from happening.

432
00:26:51.140 --> 00:26:53.369
So to wrap up this section,

433
00:26:54.700 --> 00:26:58.620
what I've shown you is that there are three signals that

434
00:26:58.660 --> 00:27:00.160
restrain the

435
00:27:01.100 --> 00:27:04.700
ability of RB deleted adenocarcinoma cells to undergo the

436
00:27:04.720 --> 00:27:05.340
transition.

437
00:27:07.200 --> 00:27:10.900
One involving YAP/TEAD activation through integrin signaling, one involving

438
00:27:10.960 --> 00:27:14.409
Notch, we don't know the molecular details, and of course, the androgen

439
00:27:14.440 --> 00:27:17.700
receptor inhibition, which sets off the process in the first

440
00:27:17.740 --> 00:27:21.349
place. Now when we give inhibitors of these

441
00:27:21.400 --> 00:27:25.100
pathways, as I've just shown you, and also add enzalutamide,

442
00:27:25.340 --> 00:27:29.160
we get this transition to occur. And as I was just telling you but

443
00:27:29.200 --> 00:27:32.990
not showing you the primary data, this process, within a matter of

444
00:27:33.140 --> 00:27:36.980
days, leads to the relocalization of FOXA1 to

445
00:27:37.000 --> 00:27:38.080
new places in

446
00:27:39.060 --> 00:27:43.000
closed chromatin that are then opened through its pioneering function

447
00:27:43.380 --> 00:27:47.120
that become the new enhancers for TEAD to bind, to turn on

448
00:27:47.160 --> 00:27:51.159
ASCL1, and to set out a full cascade of lineage transition.

449
00:27:52.500 --> 00:27:55.800
So can we do anything about this therapeutically?

450
00:27:55.860 --> 00:27:59.840
Well, today we cannot, but here's the vision I would like to paint.

451
00:28:00.700 --> 00:28:02.100
So here's the process.

452
00:28:03.320 --> 00:28:06.920
And what I've shown you is there are now three points, YAP/TEAD,

453
00:28:07.060 --> 00:28:10.660
Notch, and androgen receptor, all three of which are pharmacologically

454
00:28:10.720 --> 00:28:14.140
accessible with existing or potentially further

455
00:28:14.180 --> 00:28:18.140
developed molecules. If we wanted to do something clinically, what

456
00:28:18.320 --> 00:28:21.960
I have in mind as a first shot would be something that is going to

457
00:28:22.000 --> 00:28:25.440
sound counterintuitive. As I mentioned,

458
00:28:25.540 --> 00:28:29.460
the Novartis compound that disrupts the YAP/TEAD interaction is

459
00:28:29.500 --> 00:28:32.629
in clinical development at Novartis for other indications,

460
00:28:32.640 --> 00:28:36.280
mesotheliomas, which are dependent upon this pathway as a driver

461
00:28:36.360 --> 00:28:39.560
oncogene. But what I've just described to you is that that

462
00:28:39.620 --> 00:28:42.870
compound, if given to a patient who was in this

463
00:28:43.420 --> 00:28:47.360
lineage transition situation, might be predicted to push the

464
00:28:47.420 --> 00:28:50.380
lineage transition even faster to the neuroendocrine state.

465
00:28:51.200 --> 00:28:54.380
So I mention that as counterintuitive because, of course, that would be a much more

466
00:28:54.400 --> 00:28:58.380
aggressive phase of the disease. But the reason it's worth even talking about

467
00:28:58.620 --> 00:29:02.139
is because there's now an FDA-approved drug

468
00:29:02.580 --> 00:29:06.560
that it can engage the DLL3 cell surface receptor, a direct

469
00:29:06.600 --> 00:29:10.079
downstream target of ASCL1 in these neuroendocrine cells.

470
00:29:10.140 --> 00:29:13.269
It's a T cell engager that's been approved for its

471
00:29:13.820 --> 00:29:15.620
efficacy in small cell lung cancer.

472
00:29:16.220 --> 00:29:19.770
In prostate cancer, it's been tested but has some activity,

473
00:29:20.180 --> 00:29:23.940
but not very compelling, and I think that's because the patients have this mixed

474
00:29:23.980 --> 00:29:27.410
histology, a mix of this and a mix of this, and you see partial

475
00:29:27.460 --> 00:29:28.100
responses.

476
00:29:29.400 --> 00:29:33.060
The alternative, and perhaps more logical approach might be to push

477
00:29:33.100 --> 00:29:37.080
the tumors that are starting to go this way, all the way back to the left, where

478
00:29:37.120 --> 00:29:40.780
we have a plethora of cell surface markers that are well

479
00:29:41.100 --> 00:29:44.740
understood and for which there are therapeutic, either

480
00:29:44.820 --> 00:29:48.600
approved drugs, such as the radioligand therapy

481
00:29:48.660 --> 00:29:52.250
for PSMA, as well as drugs in development, again, T cell

482
00:29:52.280 --> 00:29:53.360
engagers. So

483
00:29:54.940 --> 00:29:56.680
to close this part,

484
00:29:57.520 --> 00:30:01.440
my thinking is that we would take advantage of

485
00:30:01.520 --> 00:30:05.160
this toggle switch to transiently give one of these

486
00:30:05.200 --> 00:30:09.120
inhibitors to push them either to the left or to the right, and then rely

487
00:30:09.200 --> 00:30:13.020
on the immune system drugs, the T cell engagers, CAR Ts that you'll hear

488
00:30:13.080 --> 00:30:14.270
about from Carl and others,

489
00:30:15.240 --> 00:30:18.260
to perhaps come in and do the final job.

490
00:30:19.380 --> 00:30:19.640
So

491
00:30:20.680 --> 00:30:24.520
what I'd like to close with is a closer look at the neuroendocrine

492
00:30:24.640 --> 00:30:25.480
state itself.

493
00:30:26.440 --> 00:30:30.120
Because even if everything I just described, which I

494
00:30:30.200 --> 00:30:33.500
admit is a bit fanciful thinking, but I've been there before in this field,

495
00:30:34.920 --> 00:30:38.640
we would want to also have something in our pocket to go after neuroendocrine

496
00:30:38.660 --> 00:30:42.600
cells directly. And I've also had the

497
00:30:42.680 --> 00:30:46.560
idea that in order for a tumor cell to

498
00:30:46.640 --> 00:30:50.610
undergo this dramatic transition, that's quite a dramatic

499
00:30:50.660 --> 00:30:54.370
parlor trick, and I suspect there might be somevulnerabilities or

500
00:30:54.410 --> 00:30:57.550
liabilities that tumor cells acquire along the way.

501
00:30:58.070 --> 00:31:01.710
So Jian Sun took on this question and started by making a

502
00:31:01.730 --> 00:31:05.330
detailed map of the chromatin landscape changes in this state

503
00:31:05.630 --> 00:31:09.589
versus then state, that state. That led to a series of candidate

504
00:31:09.670 --> 00:31:13.570
targets, including a whole suite of transcription factors, which he

505
00:31:13.670 --> 00:31:17.390
screened by CRISPR. And that CRISPR screen, which I won't show you the

506
00:31:17.430 --> 00:31:21.170
details of, led to these five hits or five

507
00:31:21.590 --> 00:31:23.310
transcription factor family hits.

508
00:31:23.650 --> 00:31:25.230
ASCL1 was expected,

509
00:31:26.290 --> 00:31:30.230
but FOXA1 is a hit because of what I showed you earlier, the dependency

510
00:31:31.210 --> 00:31:34.090
to even get there, and in other hits as well.

511
00:31:35.210 --> 00:31:37.050
So none of these can we currently

512
00:31:38.370 --> 00:31:40.530
look up in a catalog and get a chemical inhibitor.

513
00:31:40.590 --> 00:31:42.970
There are no drugs against any of these today.

514
00:31:43.820 --> 00:31:47.590
But they all must work through co-activators to activate their

515
00:31:47.730 --> 00:31:51.170
gene expression programs. So what Jian next did was a

516
00:31:51.250 --> 00:31:52.470
co-activator screen.

517
00:31:53.690 --> 00:31:57.589
And that co-activator screen, which I'm showing you the results of in sort

518
00:31:57.610 --> 00:32:01.510
of almost raw data form here, has led to an enormous

519
00:32:01.770 --> 00:32:03.260
wealth of interesting data.

520
00:32:04.300 --> 00:32:07.810
But I want to call your attention to is the red arrow.

521
00:32:07.890 --> 00:32:11.370
This is the dropout of sgRNAs

522
00:32:11.430 --> 00:32:14.690
targeting an acetyltransferase called TIP60 or

523
00:32:14.750 --> 00:32:18.710
KAT5. And you can see within each

524
00:32:18.770 --> 00:32:22.310
passage, what's plotted here are four serial passages.

525
00:32:22.350 --> 00:32:26.340
It's very fast dropout. But if you're looking carefully,

526
00:32:26.670 --> 00:32:30.490
you'll see in the bottom panel, this is the adenocarcinoma cells, an isogenic

527
00:32:30.590 --> 00:32:34.390
pair. You see dropout there. It's not quite as fast, but this is

528
00:32:34.400 --> 00:32:38.090
entirely consistent with the fact that this gene is considered an

529
00:32:38.130 --> 00:32:42.080
essential gene based on DepMap. So why would we pursue this

530
00:32:42.130 --> 00:32:45.830
any further? Well, we decided we want to look at this

531
00:32:45.890 --> 00:32:49.290
chemically. It turns out there's no viable chemical

532
00:32:49.350 --> 00:32:52.910
inhibitors of this drug that have been reported by anybody in the

533
00:32:52.970 --> 00:32:56.810
literature. So we took advantage of a trick that Jay Bradner's lab

534
00:32:56.870 --> 00:33:00.130
first developed some years ago, and that is this system

535
00:33:01.030 --> 00:33:04.450
called the dTAG system. So here the idea is you

536
00:33:04.490 --> 00:33:05.090
engineer

537
00:33:06.190 --> 00:33:08.710
a special tag into your protein of interest

538
00:33:08.950 --> 00:33:12.510
that's a hook for a degrader molecule, a

539
00:33:12.570 --> 00:33:14.970
molecular glue that will degrade that protein.

540
00:33:15.370 --> 00:33:18.990
So we engineered that into the neuroendocrine cells, the adenocarcinoma

541
00:33:19.110 --> 00:33:22.010
cells, normal prostate cells, and fibroblasts.

542
00:33:22.050 --> 00:33:25.520
And you can see in a dose response fashion, we get beautiful

543
00:33:25.630 --> 00:33:29.170
degradation of our TIP60 protein in these cells.

544
00:33:29.810 --> 00:33:33.210
But the reason I'm showing you this is we see a very dramatic shift in the

545
00:33:33.230 --> 00:33:37.150
dependency of cells on TIP60, depending

546
00:33:37.210 --> 00:33:40.930
on their lineage. So this yellow orange curve

547
00:33:42.130 --> 00:33:45.190
is the neuroendocrine cells. And you can see that we have an

548
00:33:45.250 --> 00:33:48.650
IC50 at a drug concentration that is not completely

549
00:33:48.710 --> 00:33:52.130
eliminating all of TIP60 protein in all of the cells.

550
00:33:52.190 --> 00:33:55.930
So if we could develop a small molecule inhibitor

551
00:33:56.010 --> 00:33:59.970
and perhaps bring it into the clinic, there might be a therapeutic

552
00:34:00.050 --> 00:34:00.510
index.

553
00:34:01.550 --> 00:34:01.690
So the

554
00:34:02.550 --> 00:34:06.420
next question is: What is TIP60? TIP60, as I mentioned,

555
00:34:06.490 --> 00:34:07.670
is an acetyltransferase.

556
00:34:08.630 --> 00:34:12.180
TIP60 protein in this complex is shown here, is part of

557
00:34:12.250 --> 00:34:16.170
a large mega Dalton complex that has at least 17

558
00:34:16.230 --> 00:34:20.031
subunits. And it has these three functions, the histone

559
00:34:20.051 --> 00:34:22.430
acetylation, which is mediated by this subunit.

560
00:34:22.830 --> 00:34:26.470
It's also involved in a process known as H2A,

561
00:34:26.690 --> 00:34:30.170
H2AX exchange. H2AX is a variant histone.

562
00:34:30.830 --> 00:34:34.650
And that process is carried out by this scaffold protein

563
00:34:34.670 --> 00:34:38.650
known as EP300. Which by the way, was also a hit in the screen.

564
00:34:38.670 --> 00:34:41.930
Its potency is similar to what I showed you for the

565
00:34:42.290 --> 00:34:46.031
catalytic subunit. And the complex also

566
00:34:46.091 --> 00:34:49.850
has three or four reader domain proteins, which are important in

567
00:34:49.910 --> 00:34:53.370
binding chromatin and also are potential handles for drug

568
00:34:53.410 --> 00:34:53.910
ability.

569
00:34:54.830 --> 00:34:58.290
So the next question we asked is: What's the substrate for

570
00:34:58.310 --> 00:35:02.170
TIP60 in our system? And it's very clear that it's H2AX

571
00:35:02.230 --> 00:35:02.670
itself.

572
00:35:03.970 --> 00:35:07.010
You can see complete loss of this acetylation mark, both in the

573
00:35:07.090 --> 00:35:10.229
adenocarcinoma state as well as in the neuroendocrine state.

574
00:35:10.669 --> 00:35:12.410
In data I don't have time to show you,

575
00:35:13.430 --> 00:35:17.410
we can show that this acetylation is absolutely critical for the

576
00:35:17.490 --> 00:35:19.950
activity in neuroendocrine proliferation.

577
00:35:20.330 --> 00:35:24.290
The enzymatic activity of the protein is required in order to rescue a

578
00:35:24.310 --> 00:35:28.150
knockout. And even more compelling, if you mutate these

579
00:35:28.190 --> 00:35:32.170
lysine residues, the lysine 4 and lysine 7 to

580
00:35:32.230 --> 00:35:34.060
non-acetylatable residues,

581
00:35:34.950 --> 00:35:37.010
and you cannot rescue the cells completely.

582
00:35:37.270 --> 00:35:41.230
So this is clearly a key signal that is happening

583
00:35:41.310 --> 00:35:43.190
in these cells that's driving proliferation.

584
00:35:44.110 --> 00:35:47.350
So let's go back to the transcription factors that were the hits in the screen.

585
00:35:48.170 --> 00:35:51.850
So I'm going to show you a very large heat map

586
00:35:52.250 --> 00:35:56.030
of cut-and-run experiments where we look at the chromatin localization of

587
00:35:56.070 --> 00:35:59.990
each transcription factor, the various chromatin marks, and TIP60

588
00:36:00.050 --> 00:36:03.790
itself. And the plot is organized by those

589
00:36:04.070 --> 00:36:07.630
enhancers that are open in the adeno start state versus those that are

590
00:36:07.690 --> 00:36:11.110
open in the neuroendocrine state, as defined by this ATAC plot.

591
00:36:11.870 --> 00:36:14.120
And what you can see, and you can see how much work this was,

592
00:36:15.070 --> 00:36:18.810
is there's a remarkable coincidence if you look carefully at

593
00:36:18.890 --> 00:36:19.230
each

594
00:36:20.970 --> 00:36:24.860
of these transcription factors and the corresponding marks with

595
00:36:24.890 --> 00:36:28.670
each other in each lineage. It's as if they're all on top of each other,

596
00:36:28.750 --> 00:36:32.690
working as an orchestra together to drive this transition.

597
00:36:32.770 --> 00:36:33.710
I also want to point out

598
00:36:34.770 --> 00:36:38.430
that MYC, which was a hit in the screen for dependency,

599
00:36:39.050 --> 00:36:42.090
has an interesting sort of subtext, and that is that in the

600
00:36:42.390 --> 00:36:45.550
adenocarcinoma state, it's cMYC that is the dependency.

601
00:36:45.970 --> 00:36:49.730
But in the neuroendocrine state, it's lMYC, and that's because these undergo a

602
00:36:49.830 --> 00:36:52.560
paralog shift in expression. I'll come back to

603
00:36:52.610 --> 00:36:56.108
that.So it looked like a remarkable

604
00:36:56.138 --> 00:36:57.967
coincidence of binding of all those peaks.

605
00:36:58.078 --> 00:37:01.678
If you look one by one and really carefully annotate that, some

606
00:37:01.778 --> 00:37:05.658
themes start to come out. One is that Ascl1 has the greatest overlap

607
00:37:05.678 --> 00:37:09.138
with all of the other transcription factors, and that's shown by this heat map.

608
00:37:09.638 --> 00:37:13.318
The other is that Tip60 overlaps primarily with the Myc

609
00:37:13.398 --> 00:37:13.798
peaks.

610
00:37:15.398 --> 00:37:19.018
That sets up a really interesting hypothesis, and that is, is

611
00:37:19.058 --> 00:37:21.958
Tip60 and Myc sort of closely partnered in some way?

612
00:37:21.998 --> 00:37:25.338
In other words, is Tip60 the co-activator for Myc?

613
00:37:25.718 --> 00:37:29.278
And the answer is yes. And the first clue for that is that if we did

614
00:37:29.658 --> 00:37:33.458
principal component analysis of changes in the transcriptomes within

615
00:37:33.498 --> 00:37:37.278
just a few days of knocking them down before the proliferation effects are

616
00:37:37.478 --> 00:37:40.758
seen, you see that the Tip60 and the Myc

617
00:37:41.458 --> 00:37:42.918
plots are indistinguishable.

618
00:37:44.598 --> 00:37:48.178
We can show that they bind in a complex in a coimmunoprecipitation experiment.

619
00:37:48.798 --> 00:37:52.538
And if we use the dTAG trick again to now, and this time degrade L-Myc,

620
00:37:52.878 --> 00:37:56.278
which works extremely well, you can see the loss of binding in a cut-and-run

621
00:37:56.358 --> 00:38:00.118
assay. You also, within just six hours of starting to degrade

622
00:38:00.238 --> 00:38:02.558
L-Myc, you see loss of Tip60 binding.

623
00:38:02.898 --> 00:38:05.618
So this pretty much puts a very clear

624
00:38:06.358 --> 00:38:09.978
line of evidence that Myc

625
00:38:10.258 --> 00:38:13.538
and Tip60 partner up.

626
00:38:14.218 --> 00:38:16.658
The next question is, what do they regulate?

627
00:38:17.018 --> 00:38:19.178
Well, if we take this data from over here and

628
00:38:20.598 --> 00:38:24.218
look at the gene sets that are downregulated, we see a pretty interesting

629
00:38:24.278 --> 00:38:27.658
phenomenon. First of all, the Myc and Tip60 gene sets

630
00:38:27.798 --> 00:38:30.998
only regulate cell growth and proliferation, whereas

631
00:38:31.238 --> 00:38:35.138
Ascl1 as well as Sox1 and 11 regulate

632
00:38:35.148 --> 00:38:36.428
that as well. And

633
00:38:37.318 --> 00:38:40.598
data I don't have time to show, that's through direct upregulation of Myc,

634
00:38:41.498 --> 00:38:44.438
and they also regulate the neuroendocrine identity.

635
00:38:45.038 --> 00:38:45.778
So to close,

636
00:38:47.298 --> 00:38:50.778
we went back to the dTAG system one more time to

637
00:38:50.798 --> 00:38:54.738
compare the dependency of cells in the adeno state

638
00:38:54.798 --> 00:38:58.058
versus the neuroendocrine state on their relative Myc paralog.

639
00:38:58.738 --> 00:39:02.388
And what you can see here is the degradation works in both systems,

640
00:39:02.838 --> 00:39:06.238
but we also see this dramatic shift to the left, similar to what I showed you with

641
00:39:06.258 --> 00:39:10.038
Tip60 in the neuroendocrine state, showing greater addiction on

642
00:39:10.078 --> 00:39:10.358
Myc.

643
00:39:11.638 --> 00:39:15.578
And the really surprising result here is in trying to

644
00:39:15.698 --> 00:39:18.897
sort of understand how it is that this addiction develops.

645
00:39:19.358 --> 00:39:22.018
We see a switch in the coactivator usage of Myc.

646
00:39:22.498 --> 00:39:25.658
So I showed you a minute ago that in the neuroendocrine state, if you

647
00:39:25.738 --> 00:39:29.728
degrade L-Myc, you see loss of Tip60 binding, showing that

648
00:39:29.778 --> 00:39:33.618
they are tightly coupled. But if we do the same experiment in the adeno state

649
00:39:33.678 --> 00:39:36.658
degrading c-Myc, there's no change in Tip60.

650
00:39:36.998 --> 00:39:40.738
So there's a dependence upon c-Myc in the adeno state, but it's

651
00:39:40.748 --> 00:39:42.878
through a different set of coactivators.

652
00:39:44.358 --> 00:39:45.138
So to wrap it up,

653
00:39:45.938 --> 00:39:49.718
I've shown you that the adeno state moves to the neuroendocrine state

654
00:39:49.728 --> 00:39:53.518
through a series of changes that take time, with chromatin

655
00:39:53.718 --> 00:39:56.718
rewiring driven by FoxA1 and TEAD

656
00:39:56.758 --> 00:40:00.618
relocalization. That sets a new state, which has this

657
00:40:00.658 --> 00:40:04.318
exquisite dependence upon Myc homologs, and

658
00:40:04.358 --> 00:40:06.938
a partnership with Tip60, which

659
00:40:07.818 --> 00:40:11.738
raises the very intriguing question: Is there a therapeutic index

660
00:40:11.758 --> 00:40:14.988
for targeting Myc by targeting its coactivator?

661
00:40:16.118 --> 00:40:20.038
So my last slide is to go back to what I said four years ago.

662
00:40:21.048 --> 00:40:24.778
Maybe we can beat lineage plasticity if we understand the molecular details.

663
00:40:24.818 --> 00:40:28.298
And what I've shown you is that Rb1 loss sets up the

664
00:40:28.348 --> 00:40:28.998
process.

665
00:40:29.838 --> 00:40:33.628
We use the word priming. We don't know what exactly that means molecularly,

666
00:40:33.698 --> 00:40:37.218
because at a chromatin level, there's not dramatic differences, but they're

667
00:40:37.278 --> 00:40:40.698
poised to undergo a transition if you poke them in the right way.

668
00:40:41.138 --> 00:40:44.998
And the poking here is loss of extracellular matrix engagement

669
00:40:45.018 --> 00:40:48.938
through integrin, and loss of Yap/TAD, and loss of Notch activation.

670
00:40:50.078 --> 00:40:53.698
And as I showed you, we can toggle this in the laboratory.

671
00:40:53.838 --> 00:40:57.638
We can do it convincingly in vitro. We're now trying to do it in animals.

672
00:40:58.518 --> 00:41:02.178
And then I'll conclude with the point I made on the last slide, is Tip60

673
00:41:02.218 --> 00:41:05.578
becomes quite interesting as a potential therapeutic target.

674
00:41:05.958 --> 00:41:09.258
We need to make a chemical inhibitor that has legs, and that's what we're working

675
00:41:09.318 --> 00:41:12.308
on now. Thank you for listening, and

676
00:41:13.578 --> 00:41:14.358
it's been an honor.

677
00:41:22.298 --> 00:41:24.578
Thank you, Dr. Sawyers, for that excellent talk.

678
00:41:25.638 --> 00:41:29.378
Our next speaker is Dr. Carl H. June. Dr.

679
00:41:29.618 --> 00:41:29.958
June

