00:44:38.850 --> 00:44:42.030
moving much more rapidly than it has now that we have

733
00:44:43.090 --> 00:44:46.770
a platform of cell and gene therapies to

734
00:44:46.830 --> 00:44:50.490
advance on, and that's, I think, a good message.

735
00:44:51.090 --> 00:44:54.610
When you step back right now, there are four types of CAR T cells

736
00:44:54.650 --> 00:44:58.430
being tested. I will be talking today on the upper

737
00:44:58.510 --> 00:45:02.270
left, using mostly autologous ex vivo

738
00:45:02.350 --> 00:45:06.260
manufactured CAR T cells, but also talk about box four, which

739
00:45:06.310 --> 00:45:10.180
is in vivo manufacturing of CAR cells, in this case using

740
00:45:10.470 --> 00:45:12.510
lipid nanoparticles.

741
00:45:13.810 --> 00:45:17.760
And so there are active areas in all of these, but at this point in

742
00:45:17.930 --> 00:45:21.510
2026, all FDA-approved CAR

743
00:45:21.650 --> 00:45:25.550
therapies are using autologous ex vivo manufactured cells,

744
00:45:26.630 --> 00:45:30.030
and those are for seven kinds of leukemia,

745
00:45:30.110 --> 00:45:32.210
lymphoma, and myeloma.

746
00:45:33.390 --> 00:45:37.009
And now we also have tumor-infiltrating lymphocytes and

747
00:45:37.070 --> 00:45:41.050
T-cell receptor redirected T cells approved as well.

748
00:45:41.690 --> 00:45:45.450
The issue here primarily is scale and complexity of

749
00:45:45.530 --> 00:45:48.190
manufacturing. But the other one really is,

750
00:45:49.190 --> 00:45:52.590
as I'll discuss, how do we get these to work in solid

751
00:45:52.670 --> 00:45:56.550
cancers? And for that, there's lots of work in making

752
00:45:56.590 --> 00:45:59.130
next-generation CAR cells.

753
00:46:00.290 --> 00:46:04.250
And I'll show today work using dual and tandem-targeted

754
00:46:04.410 --> 00:46:07.970
CAR cells and then so-called armored CAR cells that

755
00:46:08.310 --> 00:46:11.550
are CAR T cells that not only are redirected but also

756
00:46:13.050 --> 00:46:15.670
express cytokines in this case.

757
00:46:16.530 --> 00:46:19.970
So we first showed the idea of taking a

758
00:46:20.010 --> 00:46:23.830
C19 CAR cell and armoring it with a cytokine called

759
00:46:23.930 --> 00:46:27.010
IL-18. This is a cytokine made in the

760
00:46:27.130 --> 00:46:31.030
NLRP3 inflammasome. It has its own checkpoint, which

761
00:46:31.050 --> 00:46:34.990
is IL-18. And we picked that because we thought it might decrease

762
00:46:35.010 --> 00:46:37.650
the chance of cytokine release syndrome.

763
00:46:38.350 --> 00:46:41.130
So we conducted a first-in-human trial in patients

764
00:46:42.050 --> 00:46:45.870
with lymphoma who were either CAR refractory or who

765
00:46:45.910 --> 00:46:49.460
had relapsed after CAR T-cell treatment with commercially approved

766
00:46:49.510 --> 00:46:53.150
CARs. And we had really a quite remarkable

767
00:46:53.210 --> 00:46:56.670
finding in this trial. Those armored CARs resulted in a

768
00:46:56.890 --> 00:47:00.570
75% complete response rate in these

769
00:47:00.590 --> 00:47:04.310
patients and with no real change in toxicity

770
00:47:04.430 --> 00:47:07.990
from what we've seen with the FDA-approved CARs.

771
00:47:09.130 --> 00:47:12.850
The disappointing aspect is that down here, our

772
00:47:12.950 --> 00:47:16.830
finding for this was reported in 2017 in mice

773
00:47:16.890 --> 00:47:20.770
that we could armor these CAR cells, but it took until last year until we

774
00:47:20.850 --> 00:47:22.890
could actually get this reported.

775
00:47:22.950 --> 00:47:26.050
We need to make this a more rapid, iterative process.

776
00:47:27.770 --> 00:47:31.530
So to summarize where we are with CAR T cells in

777
00:47:31.570 --> 00:47:33.890
blood cancer, there's been a lot of progress.

778
00:47:34.010 --> 00:47:37.100
About 60,000 patients have been treated,

779
00:47:38.230 --> 00:47:42.070
and there's lots of work in other kinds of cell therapies,

780
00:47:42.130 --> 00:47:45.750
such as TCR T cells and allogeneic CAR

781
00:47:45.830 --> 00:47:47.510
cells and NK cells,

782
00:47:48.550 --> 00:47:51.790
and then a lot of work and then in scaling out the

783
00:47:51.830 --> 00:47:52.620
manufacturing.

784
00:47:53.490 --> 00:47:56.850
So blood cancer is relatively simple in

785
00:47:57.470 --> 00:48:01.410
its tumor microenvironment compared to solid tumors, where

786
00:48:01.450 --> 00:48:04.610
we haven't had dramatic responses in general with CAR cells.

787
00:48:05.030 --> 00:48:06.430
And there's a lot of reasons for that.

788
00:48:06.490 --> 00:48:09.170
The tumor microenvironment is more established.

789
00:48:09.200 --> 00:48:12.500
It has more checkpoints immunologically, and it also has

790
00:48:12.530 --> 00:48:16.320
metabolic checkpoints that the blood cancers

791
00:48:16.350 --> 00:48:17.010
don't face.

792
00:48:17.890 --> 00:48:20.430
So where are we with solid cancers?

793
00:48:21.730 --> 00:48:24.270
These are some of the targets shown here on the left,

794
00:48:25.270 --> 00:48:28.810
and I'll be focusing on mesothelin, a tumor-associated antigen in

795
00:48:28.890 --> 00:48:32.050
pancreatic cancer and ovarian cancer, and in

796
00:48:32.470 --> 00:48:34.030
EGFR variant III and

797
00:48:34.930 --> 00:48:38.590
glioblastoma. But the most advanced testing is being

798
00:48:38.650 --> 00:48:42.410
done in a tight junction protein called

799
00:48:42.450 --> 00:48:43.810
claudin 18.2.

800
00:48:44.830 --> 00:48:47.990
And I'll summarize this Phase 2 trial here.

801
00:48:48.190 --> 00:48:52.150
So in China, a trial was conducted in

802
00:48:52.190 --> 00:48:54.690
patients with refractory gastroesophageal

803
00:48:55.470 --> 00:48:57.050
cancer targeting

804
00:48:58.030 --> 00:49:01.480
claudin 18.2 with autologous CAR cells.

805
00:49:01.950 --> 00:49:05.610
This is the only randomized controlled trial now yet

806
00:49:05.650 --> 00:49:08.540
reported with CAR T cells. And what they found

807
00:49:08.610 --> 00:49:12.482
wasQuite promising. As you can see, the overall response rate

808
00:49:12.962 --> 00:49:16.782
with the CAR cells compared to a standard of care therapy.

809
00:49:17.742 --> 00:49:21.312
And so this is really promising. The disappointing

810
00:49:21.422 --> 00:49:24.522
aspect is that it's not durable. The average

811
00:49:24.882 --> 00:49:28.122
prolongation of PFS was about two months.

812
00:49:28.162 --> 00:49:32.142
So we have a foot in the door now in solid cancers with CAR cells,

813
00:49:32.242 --> 00:49:36.102
but we need durability to be improved.

814
00:49:38.182 --> 00:49:41.232
So with that, I'll turn to what we're doing at the University of

815
00:49:41.282 --> 00:49:44.302
Pennsylvania in our institute.

816
00:49:45.111 --> 00:49:48.892
And first focus on glioblastoma and trials led by

817
00:49:49.162 --> 00:49:49.862
Don Rork

818
00:49:50.782 --> 00:49:53.402
and his team, and then move on to

819
00:49:53.462 --> 00:49:56.362
mesothelin as a target in

820
00:49:58.262 --> 00:49:59.682
abdominal malignancies. So

821
00:50:00.522 --> 00:50:04.312
in glioblastoma, we've now conducted three trials at the University of

822
00:50:04.382 --> 00:50:05.042
Pennsylvania.

823
00:50:05.962 --> 00:50:09.052
The initial trial targeted mutated EGFR,

824
00:50:10.282 --> 00:50:13.962
and we used intravenously administered CAR T-cells.

825
00:50:14.002 --> 00:50:17.782
And in that trial, we saw no responses whatsoever.

826
00:50:18.022 --> 00:50:21.862
So now we have dealt with that by two changes, and

827
00:50:21.942 --> 00:50:25.622
one is making a bicistronic construct that targets both

828
00:50:25.682 --> 00:50:29.622
mutated EGFR in glioblastoma, which is

829
00:50:29.702 --> 00:50:33.342
present in about 60% of cases. And as well as

830
00:50:33.682 --> 00:50:37.002
IL-13 receptor alpha 2, which is present in about

831
00:50:37.222 --> 00:50:39.782
75% of glioblastoma.

832
00:50:41.602 --> 00:50:45.542
Both of these are expressed in the same autologous T-cell so that we

833
00:50:45.582 --> 00:50:47.622
have dual targeting. And,

834
00:50:49.862 --> 00:50:53.482
we've now reported both an initial pilot study of six patients and the

835
00:50:53.522 --> 00:50:57.382
full 18 patients treated at the

836
00:50:57.402 --> 00:51:01.082
University of Pennsylvania on this IIT trial.

837
00:51:01.162 --> 00:51:03.722
So it's a pretty standard trial design.

838
00:51:03.762 --> 00:51:07.582
The patients have to have refractory glioblastoma, be adults.

839
00:51:08.222 --> 00:51:08.702
And then,

840
00:51:09.522 --> 00:51:12.962
we've tested several dose levels, with very

841
00:51:13.062 --> 00:51:16.142
small amounts of CAR cells, five million cells, which

842
00:51:16.762 --> 00:51:18.682
was usually what we use in mice.

843
00:51:19.642 --> 00:51:22.862
And we're now giving these, via an omaya reservoir.

844
00:51:23.302 --> 00:51:26.762
Our initial treatments were through intravenous administration.

845
00:51:26.862 --> 00:51:28.642
So the main change here being

846
00:51:28.702 --> 00:51:32.662
intra-CNS delivery

847
00:51:32.782 --> 00:51:36.642
and as well as dual targeting now. And we found in this trial

848
00:51:36.722 --> 00:51:40.582
a dose-dependent PK in the blood after giving

849
00:51:41.442 --> 00:51:44.982
from five million up to 25 million cells.

850
00:51:45.082 --> 00:51:48.802
And an area under the curve dose-dependent

851
00:51:48.822 --> 00:51:52.671
increase over the first month after treatment, looking at the PK and

852
00:51:52.742 --> 00:51:56.362
cerebral spinal fluid. And then in the blood, we find

853
00:51:57.082 --> 00:51:58.831
very low levels in the blood of the

854
00:52:00.202 --> 00:52:04.182
omaya administered cells, but with some leakage into the blood or

855
00:52:04.242 --> 00:52:05.462
trafficking out from

856
00:52:06.402 --> 00:52:09.202
in the highest doses treated patients.

857
00:52:09.262 --> 00:52:09.421
So

858
00:52:10.302 --> 00:52:14.122
we found for the first time now very encouraging findings

859
00:52:14.182 --> 00:52:17.502
on imaging. And these are the first three patients

860
00:52:17.562 --> 00:52:21.222
treated with gadolinium-enhanced PET

861
00:52:21.342 --> 00:52:25.202
scans. And this first patient here had a day before

862
00:52:25.262 --> 00:52:29.102
treatment an image showed multifocal glioblastoma with the

863
00:52:29.142 --> 00:52:33.002
red and green arrows. And within two days, you can see

864
00:52:33.122 --> 00:52:34.802
a massive improvement here.

865
00:52:35.802 --> 00:52:37.842
And we didn't see this in the first two trials.

866
00:52:38.482 --> 00:52:41.902
And we saw changes like this in all three patients

867
00:52:42.622 --> 00:52:45.462
treated. So a very exciting change.

868
00:52:45.951 --> 00:52:49.462
The swimmer's plot here, from Steve Bagley, sent to me

869
00:52:49.472 --> 00:52:52.842
yesterday. This is updated until this month.

870
00:52:52.852 --> 00:52:56.442
There's now in the 13 of 18 patients who had measurable

871
00:52:56.522 --> 00:52:58.182
disease, there's been

872
00:52:58.682 --> 00:53:02.482
responses observed. And with the

873
00:53:02.562 --> 00:53:06.342
best responses by the RENO criteria of two

874
00:53:06.422 --> 00:53:09.602
PRs and an overall disease control rate of about

875
00:53:09.702 --> 00:53:13.362
70%. Now, these are the 18 patients on this

876
00:53:13.382 --> 00:53:14.162
swimmer's plot.

877
00:53:15.382 --> 00:53:15.742
And

878
00:53:16.602 --> 00:53:20.422
the first patient or patient three here now is out 34 months,

879
00:53:20.682 --> 00:53:22.102
and his tumor has not recurred

880
00:53:23.222 --> 00:53:26.642
after that initial single treatment.

881
00:53:26.722 --> 00:53:29.921
So we're seeing as these data mature, an improvement in

882
00:53:30.382 --> 00:53:34.142
survival rate. This is much different than the initial two trials we

883
00:53:34.182 --> 00:53:37.982
conducted. So how is that that it has improved,

884
00:53:38.502 --> 00:53:42.262
the same kinds of tumors? And Dana Silver Bush and her group are

885
00:53:42.282 --> 00:53:45.962
looking at this by studying CSF recurrent

886
00:53:46.042 --> 00:53:49.562
sampling and the tumor biopsies in patients

887
00:53:50.522 --> 00:53:54.422
after treatment to look for correlates of response and

888
00:53:54.462 --> 00:53:58.062
resistance. And the first thing she's found is that there are

889
00:53:58.122 --> 00:54:01.402
improvements in natural killer cells in the tumor

890
00:54:01.482 --> 00:54:05.292
microenvironment, and there's both a discovery cohort and a

891
00:54:05.362 --> 00:54:09.202
validation cohort. But the responding patients have much

892
00:54:09.242 --> 00:54:12.602
higher NK cells in the tumor microenvironment than

893
00:54:13.662 --> 00:54:17.602
the non-responding patients, and that correlates with PFS

894
00:54:18.062 --> 00:54:21.922
in this group of patients. She's also found a negative

895
00:54:21.962 --> 00:54:23.422
correlative response, and that's

896
00:54:24.302 --> 00:54:26.122
Tregs. Regulatory T-cells

897
00:54:27.162 --> 00:54:29.482
are inversely correlated with

898
00:54:30.942 --> 00:54:32.022
survival and

899
00:54:32.902 --> 00:54:36.742
changes in tumor volume here, and also

900
00:54:36.802 --> 00:54:40.382
here in PFS. So the patients with the most

901
00:54:43.402 --> 00:54:45.022
Tregs do the worst.

902
00:54:46.142 --> 00:54:49.822
So those are two correlatives at my point.

903
00:54:50.162 --> 00:54:53.882
And then just yesterday, we got this recent spatial

904
00:54:53.922 --> 00:54:55.462
biology profiling

905
00:54:56.382 --> 00:54:58.742
done by Wes Wilson and Andrew Rack at Penn

906
00:54:58.802 --> 00:55:02.510
takingbiopsy specimens, in this case,

907
00:55:02.610 --> 00:55:06.110
six to eight patients after treatment, and then using a new

908
00:55:06.150 --> 00:55:09.570
platform from 10x Genomics called Atera, where you can

909
00:55:09.610 --> 00:55:13.530
do on this whole transcriptome analysis.

910
00:55:14.050 --> 00:55:14.780
When you do that, the

911
00:55:16.430 --> 00:55:19.840
UMAPs look like this, with four identified

912
00:55:19.850 --> 00:55:23.550
populations of cells with a tumor, and then

913
00:55:23.610 --> 00:55:27.370
glial cells, myeloid cells, and the smallest compartment being T and

914
00:55:27.590 --> 00:55:28.370
NK cells.

915
00:55:29.250 --> 00:55:32.910
In this middle panel, what we see is that the amount of NK

916
00:55:33.010 --> 00:55:36.650
cells increases on the spatial biology from

917
00:55:36.710 --> 00:55:40.690
14% at baseline on average to 22%

918
00:55:41.770 --> 00:55:45.470
after treatment in five of six of these paired

919
00:55:45.530 --> 00:55:49.450
treatments. On the right-hand panel here is, unfortunately, it's a

920
00:55:49.470 --> 00:55:53.410
disappointment, where we see a resistance mechanism

921
00:55:53.420 --> 00:55:56.950
where the tumor cell state itself is changing

922
00:55:57.830 --> 00:55:59.550
from its initial

923
00:56:00.470 --> 00:56:02.950
state to a more mesenchymal-like state with,

924
00:56:03.910 --> 00:56:07.230
on these gene signatures, less EGFR and aquaporin 4

925
00:56:07.250 --> 00:56:11.070
expression. And the tumor cells are not randomly

926
00:56:11.250 --> 00:56:13.330
distributed in the tumor microenvironment.

927
00:56:13.410 --> 00:56:17.140
They're around myeloid cells, which are probably shielding

928
00:56:17.170 --> 00:56:19.610
them and contributing to resistance.

929
00:56:19.770 --> 00:56:23.350
So this is not unlike some of what you just saw in prostate cancer.

930
00:56:23.450 --> 00:56:27.290
Lineage plasticity can unfortunately be a major cause

931
00:56:27.370 --> 00:56:31.150
of resistance. So we're seeing promise and advances

932
00:56:31.190 --> 00:56:33.990
with CAR cells in glioblastoma, in

933
00:56:34.010 --> 00:56:37.940
stepwise-driven, small numbers of patients, but

934
00:56:38.010 --> 00:56:40.370
engineering around resistance mechanisms.

935
00:56:40.770 --> 00:56:44.130
Multi-epitope dual targeting has really improved

936
00:56:44.190 --> 00:56:47.710
responses combined with local regional delivery

937
00:56:47.850 --> 00:56:51.630
in glioblastoma, and there's many more, I think,

938
00:56:51.710 --> 00:56:55.650
iterations required now to make durable responses

939
00:56:55.850 --> 00:56:58.830
in most patients. But I think we have our foot in the door.

940
00:56:59.610 --> 00:57:02.810
What I'd like to do now is shift to mesothelin as a

941
00:57:02.850 --> 00:57:05.770
tumor-associated antigen target.

942
00:57:05.810 --> 00:57:09.470
Mesothelin's a GPI-linked protein that's overexpressed

943
00:57:09.570 --> 00:57:13.270
in nearly all pancreatic cancers, in serous

944
00:57:13.310 --> 00:57:16.390
ovarian cancer, and in

945
00:57:16.430 --> 00:57:17.610
mesotheliomas.

946
00:57:18.550 --> 00:57:22.520
So we've been doing trials here for 15 years with that as a

947
00:57:22.570 --> 00:57:26.400
CAR target, and we've uncovered two mechanisms of resistance,

948
00:57:26.590 --> 00:57:29.710
one being impaired CAR T cell

949
00:57:30.250 --> 00:57:33.930
infiltration into the pancreatic tumor

950
00:57:33.990 --> 00:57:34.950
microenvironment.

951
00:57:36.230 --> 00:57:39.970
And I'll be coming back to this. The other aspect we've seen

952
00:57:40.110 --> 00:57:43.590
is the induction of rapid T cell exhaustion

953
00:57:44.090 --> 00:57:47.830
in the CAR T cells that actually manage to get into the

954
00:57:48.210 --> 00:57:51.960
tumor microenvironment. These have not been issues in blood cancer.

955
00:57:53.010 --> 00:57:56.850
So in the very first trial we did with Greg

956
00:57:56.890 --> 00:58:00.690
Beatty at Penn targeting metastatic pancreatic cancer, we had,

957
00:58:01.330 --> 00:58:04.990
looking at these six patients, looking at imaging

958
00:58:05.170 --> 00:58:08.190
after treatment, some responses in patients, with the best

959
00:58:09.150 --> 00:58:11.930
being a month after treatment. This patient here

960
00:58:13.110 --> 00:58:16.690
with pancreatic cancer after a tolerance

961
00:58:16.710 --> 00:58:19.630
mesothelin-specific CAR T cells.

962
00:58:20.110 --> 00:58:23.910
At baseline, this patient had widely metastatic disease in the liver,

963
00:58:24.570 --> 00:58:28.250
and he also had in the body of his unresected primary mass.

964
00:58:28.810 --> 00:58:32.670
A month later, we had a really gratifying result in the

965
00:58:32.710 --> 00:58:36.690
liver, and you can see that here as well on imaging.

966
00:58:36.710 --> 00:58:40.530
But paradoxically, the primary pancreatic tumor actually progressed

967
00:58:40.570 --> 00:58:41.350
during that time.

968
00:58:42.350 --> 00:58:45.210
So the metastatic lesions were more sensitive

969
00:58:45.270 --> 00:58:49.250
than the primary, and that patient progressed

970
00:58:49.260 --> 00:58:52.290
and died rapidly. So we've been studying that

971
00:58:53.930 --> 00:58:55.810
as mixed response, and

972
00:58:56.610 --> 00:59:00.230
this is work that Angela Aznar did in my lab with Shelly

973
00:59:00.250 --> 00:59:04.050
Berger's lab at Penn, where we looked in vitro at in these

974
00:59:04.090 --> 00:59:07.890
mesothelin CAR T cells ex vivo and repeatedly

975
00:59:07.970 --> 00:59:08.800
stimulating them,

976
00:59:09.620 --> 00:59:13.350
the CAR T cells, by repeated additions of a

977
00:59:13.410 --> 00:59:16.830
KRAS mutant pancreatic tumor line.

978
00:59:16.850 --> 00:59:20.550
And what we found was rapid and widespread transcriptomic

979
00:59:21.150 --> 00:59:24.150
and epigenetic shifts in the CAR T cells

980
00:59:25.230 --> 00:59:29.079
that were published here. We found a 30-gene signature

981
00:59:30.170 --> 00:59:34.030
in the cells that became inactive, and we also found the induction of

982
00:59:34.090 --> 00:59:38.010
transcription factors in the CAR T cells, such as SOX4

983
00:59:38.050 --> 00:59:40.710
and ID3, that aren't in healthy T cells.

984
00:59:41.450 --> 00:59:45.270
So we're now looking at ways of getting around

985
00:59:45.310 --> 00:59:48.660
this. So we've been working with targeting the CAFs,

986
00:59:48.850 --> 00:59:52.740
