1226
01:14:56.072 --> 01:15:00.032
And so we can get started. So our research is focusing on addressing this

1227
01:15:00.072 --> 01:15:03.592
limitation that only around 20% of all human proteins are

1228
01:15:03.611 --> 01:15:05.392
addressable with small molecules.

1229
01:15:05.432 --> 01:15:09.332
And the reason for this is, I would argue that as a community, we've

1230
01:15:09.392 --> 01:15:13.312
adapted a very inhibitor-centric mindset, meaning that we

1231
01:15:13.412 --> 01:15:16.912
want to fashion small organic molecules that bind to

1232
01:15:16.952 --> 01:15:20.672
hydrophobic pockets on target proteins with the intent of functionally

1233
01:15:20.712 --> 01:15:22.372
antagonizing those proteins.

1234
01:15:23.432 --> 01:15:27.352
And so the problem is that the remaining 80% of the human proteome simply lack

1235
01:15:27.392 --> 01:15:29.612
such ligatable and biochemically active pockets.

1236
01:15:30.452 --> 01:15:34.052
So the question that emerges is how can we pursue these remaining targets?

1237
01:15:34.092 --> 01:15:37.332
And our approach is to try to completely shift

1238
01:15:37.652 --> 01:15:41.512
perspective and move away from trying to identify small molecules that bind to a

1239
01:15:41.572 --> 01:15:45.252
target and inhibit its function towards small molecules that act as

1240
01:15:45.512 --> 01:15:47.412
what we like to refer as chemical neomorphs.

1241
01:15:47.932 --> 01:15:51.792
Small molecules that change the function of a target protein and endow them with

1242
01:15:52.032 --> 01:15:55.112
new functionalities that evolution hasn't taught them.

1243
01:15:56.852 --> 01:16:00.612
So our strategy is to capitalize on the principle that proximity

1244
01:16:00.632 --> 01:16:03.832
induction is a fundamental regulatory principle in biology.

1245
01:16:03.872 --> 01:16:07.672
So biology very much works by regulating proximity of

1246
01:16:07.712 --> 01:16:10.712
macromolecules. If you think about the molecular scale, thinking about how

1247
01:16:11.112 --> 01:16:13.842
transcription regulation or signal transduction works.

1248
01:16:14.652 --> 01:16:18.292
But also on the cellular level, we think about immune activation, also

1249
01:16:18.332 --> 01:16:20.352
processes such as metastasis formation.

1250
01:16:21.692 --> 01:16:23.922
So what does it have to do with drug discovery?

1251
01:16:24.032 --> 01:16:27.632
Well, we do know since a very long time that small molecules can

1252
01:16:27.692 --> 01:16:29.532
induce protein-protein interactions.

1253
01:16:30.372 --> 01:16:34.252
And we also know since a long time with using synthetic ligands and

1254
01:16:34.292 --> 01:16:37.932
using tagged proteins, that inducing the proximity of

1255
01:16:38.032 --> 01:16:41.492
proteins can be sufficient to prompt a biologically downstream

1256
01:16:41.532 --> 01:16:45.132
response. And this has been very elegantly shown for processes

1257
01:16:45.532 --> 01:16:47.452
as diverse as signal transduction,

1258
01:16:48.312 --> 01:16:50.652
cell death induction, also nuclear import.

1259
01:16:52.812 --> 01:16:56.472
So we can conclude that by stabilizing protein-protein interactions, small

1260
01:16:56.512 --> 01:16:59.892
molecules can indeed endow proteins with new functionalities.

1261
01:17:01.112 --> 01:17:05.052
And this is also exactly the principle that targeted protein degradation

1262
01:17:05.092 --> 01:17:09.012
is built on. It's built on small molecules that induce proximity between

1263
01:17:09.072 --> 01:17:13.002
an E3 ubiquitin ligase, a member of the cellular degradation machinery, and

1264
01:17:13.002 --> 01:17:15.742
a target protein of interest that is typically disease-causing.

1265
01:17:16.652 --> 01:17:20.492
And so this can be done, for instance, by bifunctional molecules, so-called

1266
01:17:20.512 --> 01:17:24.302
PROTACs. These are molecules that were innovated by Craig Crews and Ray Deshaies,

1267
01:17:24.712 --> 01:17:27.672
which are bifunctional, meaning that they have two arms with which they

1268
01:17:27.752 --> 01:17:31.652
simultaneously ligand the E3 ligase and the target protein of interest,

1269
01:17:32.032 --> 01:17:35.932
induce proximity, cause target ubiquitination, and degradation by the

1270
01:17:35.992 --> 01:17:36.632
proteasome.

1271
01:17:37.932 --> 01:17:41.812
So the drawback of these early designs was that these PROTACs were peptidic

1272
01:17:41.852 --> 01:17:45.101
in nature, meaning that there was a limited efficacy that

1273
01:17:45.112 --> 01:17:48.002
prevented in vivo application of this

1274
01:17:48.012 --> 01:17:51.832
technology. So back then, when joining Jay Bradner's lab as a

1275
01:17:51.932 --> 01:17:55.912
postdoc, we capitalized on the finding by Hiroshi Handa and his

1276
01:17:55.932 --> 01:17:59.732
team, namely that the small molecule thalidomide has

1277
01:18:00.092 --> 01:18:00.612
an E3

1278
01:18:01.632 --> 01:18:04.712
ligase called cereblon as its endogenous binding partner.

1279
01:18:05.712 --> 01:18:09.132
So based on that knowledge, we could fashion bifunctional small

1280
01:18:09.152 --> 01:18:12.912
molecules that, on the one hand, bind to the E3

1281
01:18:12.932 --> 01:18:16.712
ligase cereblon, and on the other hand, bind to the

1282
01:18:16.732 --> 01:18:20.672
bromodomain of BET4, a protein that you'll hear more of during that

1283
01:18:20.732 --> 01:18:20.992
talk.

1284
01:18:21.952 --> 01:18:25.292
And so we were very pleased to see that with this molecule, when we treat leukemia

1285
01:18:25.372 --> 01:18:29.252
cells, we saw immediate and acute degradation in the nanomolar range.

1286
01:18:30.032 --> 01:18:33.752
And most importantly, we could also, with a single application in tumor-bearing

1287
01:18:33.872 --> 01:18:37.592
animals, detect BET4 degradation inside the tumor.

1288
01:18:38.572 --> 01:18:42.192
And so together with work from, again, Craig Crews and also Alessio Ciulli,

1289
01:18:42.592 --> 01:18:46.352
also involving the E3 ligase VHL, this really set the stage

1290
01:18:46.632 --> 01:18:49.172
for a broad therapeutic exploration of that space.

1291
01:18:50.832 --> 01:18:54.632
So today, there's more than 25 PROTACs in human

1292
01:18:54.692 --> 01:18:55.722
clinical investigation,

1293
01:18:56.752 --> 01:19:00.612
mostly in oncology. And I think they've also really redefined what we

1294
01:19:00.672 --> 01:19:04.312
consider drug-like. These are molecules that are now made routinely

1295
01:19:04.752 --> 01:19:08.052
orally bioavailable, and there's a lot of excitement in that

1296
01:19:08.132 --> 01:19:12.036
field.Nevertheless, I think it's also fair to point out that there

1297
01:19:12.056 --> 01:19:15.856
are certain limitations in the PROTAC technology, and this is particularly

1298
01:19:15.916 --> 01:19:19.456
when the target that we want to eliminate has large

1299
01:19:19.476 --> 01:19:22.016
intrinsically disordered regions that it's hard to bind.

1300
01:19:22.096 --> 01:19:25.896
Because fundamentally, remember, a PROTAC still needs to bind to the target protein

1301
01:19:25.956 --> 01:19:26.996
that we want to eliminate.

1302
01:19:28.636 --> 01:19:32.276
But luckily, this is a limitation that is addressed by another

1303
01:19:32.316 --> 01:19:35.866
modality within targeted protein degradation, the so-called molecular

1304
01:19:35.936 --> 01:19:36.636
gludegrades.

1305
01:19:37.576 --> 01:19:41.276
And so molecular gludegrades, I think, really got a boost in the field when

1306
01:19:41.456 --> 01:19:45.446
Ben Ebert's lab and Bill Kilian's lab were studying the mechanism of this

1307
01:19:45.676 --> 01:19:48.976
very prominent anti-myeloma drug, lenalidomide.

1308
01:19:49.226 --> 01:19:52.296
And so what they identified is that when lenalidomide binds cereblon,

1309
01:19:53.096 --> 01:19:56.676
it also creates a new substrate interface, which causes the

1310
01:19:56.716 --> 01:20:00.616
dimerization or the induced proximity to different zinc finger transcription

1311
01:20:00.676 --> 01:20:04.566
factors, such as ICSRF1 and ICSRF3, inducing,

1312
01:20:04.696 --> 01:20:07.516
again, the ubiquitination and degradation by the proteasome.

1313
01:20:08.176 --> 01:20:10.476
The important difference to PROTACs is that here,

1314
01:20:11.496 --> 01:20:15.316
lenalidomide or this class of IMiD drugs, they don't bind to these zinc

1315
01:20:15.356 --> 01:20:16.966
finger transcription factors in isolation.

1316
01:20:17.256 --> 01:20:20.956
They simply bind to the ligase, reshape its surface, and this is

1317
01:20:20.996 --> 01:20:24.536
sufficient to orchestrate several protein-protein interactions between the ligase

1318
01:20:24.576 --> 01:20:25.776
and the transcription factor.

1319
01:20:27.296 --> 01:20:30.676
So with those studies and related studies, the field was really presented

1320
01:20:31.076 --> 01:20:34.936
with almost a holy grail blueprint because we had an FDA-approved

1321
01:20:35.356 --> 01:20:36.696
medicine that was then

1322
01:20:37.536 --> 01:20:40.956
identified to induce the degradation of a truly unligandable,

1323
01:20:41.076 --> 01:20:44.996
undruggable protein. And that set a lot of motivation for

1324
01:20:45.036 --> 01:20:48.636
the field for us and others to really think about new discovery

1325
01:20:48.676 --> 01:20:52.616
approaches, to think about new mechanisms, and to expand the scope

1326
01:20:52.656 --> 01:20:56.616
of molecular gludegrades to new targets and new E3 ligases.

1327
01:20:56.656 --> 01:21:00.316
And so over the next couple of slides, I want to share with you a couple of

1328
01:21:00.356 --> 01:21:04.116
vignettes of work that my group has been contributing in this space.

1329
01:21:05.356 --> 01:21:09.336
So we developed several approaches to purposefully identify molecular

1330
01:21:09.376 --> 01:21:12.656
gludegrades. First, I want to introduce a phenotypic approach,

1331
01:21:13.476 --> 01:21:17.036
where Christina Maiorano, former postdoc in my lab who now is leading her

1332
01:21:17.076 --> 01:21:21.036
independent group at the IRB in Barcelona, set out initially to map

1333
01:21:21.116 --> 01:21:24.176
all genes that are required for small molecule degraders to work.

1334
01:21:24.226 --> 01:21:27.996
And this led to the identification of a gene called UBE2M,

1335
01:21:28.356 --> 01:21:29.946
which acts as a general light switch.

1336
01:21:29.996 --> 01:21:33.776
It controls the activity of more than 200 E3 ligase in any given cell.

1337
01:21:34.676 --> 01:21:38.296
And this allowed us to set up phenotypic discovery approaches, where we would test

1338
01:21:38.316 --> 01:21:41.956
libraries of compounds in cells that are wild type for UBE2M and cells that are

1339
01:21:41.996 --> 01:21:45.916
mutant for UBE2M. And amongst others, this allowed us to identify

1340
01:21:46.116 --> 01:21:50.016
a novel molecular glue mechanism where a small molecule induces

1341
01:21:50.036 --> 01:21:53.596
the proximity between a kinase, a CDK12,

1342
01:21:54.356 --> 01:21:56.856
and DDB1, an adaptor of an E3 ligase.

1343
01:21:57.416 --> 01:22:00.836
And this leads then to the ubiquitination and degradation of the

1344
01:22:00.896 --> 01:22:04.805
undruggable protein cycling K, which typically partners up with

1345
01:22:04.896 --> 01:22:08.216
CDK12 and regulates its activity.

1346
01:22:08.336 --> 01:22:12.116
So in a more recent study and in a more target-centric study

1347
01:22:12.176 --> 01:22:15.776
that we collaborated with Michael Erb, who led these studies,

1348
01:22:16.196 --> 01:22:19.436
the goal was to move away from these phenotypic approaches towards more

1349
01:22:19.446 --> 01:22:23.296
target-centric approaches. And basically, find ways of how we can turn a

1350
01:22:23.336 --> 01:22:26.436
binder of a target protein into a molecular gludegrade.

1351
01:22:27.036 --> 01:22:30.756
And so what Michael's team did is, again, leveraging this bromodomain

1352
01:22:30.796 --> 01:22:34.376
binder of BET4 and perform high-throughput chemistry, systematically

1353
01:22:34.436 --> 01:22:38.216
derivatizing what we call the exit vector, which is the outward-facing part of the

1354
01:22:38.236 --> 01:22:38.896
small molecule,

1355
01:22:39.856 --> 01:22:43.706
and making a library of more than 3,000 analogs with high-throughput chemistry, and

1356
01:22:43.736 --> 01:22:47.335
then directly testing them in cellular degradation assays.

1357
01:22:47.416 --> 01:22:50.996
So basically what Michael and his team did is that they systematically

1358
01:22:51.076 --> 01:22:54.876
adapted the surface of BET4 with a hypothesis that one of these

1359
01:22:54.896 --> 01:22:58.676
chemical modifications would stabilize a latent interaction with a

1360
01:22:58.756 --> 01:23:02.396
yet to be identified E3 ligase to cause its ubiquitination and

1361
01:23:02.456 --> 01:23:03.096
degradation.

1362
01:23:03.936 --> 01:23:07.496
And so we then had to find this particular molecule called

1363
01:23:07.736 --> 01:23:11.316
DHTC3 and found that this induces the

1364
01:23:11.336 --> 01:23:14.396
degradation of BET4 by co-opting a ligase called

1365
01:23:14.496 --> 01:23:18.256
FBXO3 which up to this point has not been addressed for targeted

1366
01:23:18.316 --> 01:23:19.736
protein degradation purposes.

1367
01:23:22.136 --> 01:23:25.696
As a next example, this is a collaboration with Alessia Ciulli in Dundee.

1368
01:23:26.136 --> 01:23:30.116
I want to share with you how by deeply characterizing this bifunctional

1369
01:23:30.155 --> 01:23:34.116
molecule that you see here called IBG-1, we identified a new

1370
01:23:34.176 --> 01:23:37.096
modality in targeted protein degradation.

1371
01:23:37.336 --> 01:23:41.256
So this molecule was initially reported in the patent literature by Mitsubishi

1372
01:23:41.296 --> 01:23:45.276
Pharma. And you again see this is clearly a bifunctional molecule, again

1373
01:23:45.336 --> 01:23:48.256
binding to BET4 with one arm. And then it has this

1374
01:23:48.896 --> 01:23:52.576
so-called arylsulfonamide on the other side that was known to

1375
01:23:52.636 --> 01:23:55.596
bind to a particular E3 ligase called DCAF15.

1376
01:23:56.516 --> 01:24:00.056
We tested this molecule and found that it is exquisitely potent in cells,

1377
01:24:00.756 --> 01:24:04.416
but then got interested because when we take cells where we have

1378
01:24:04.456 --> 01:24:07.906
deleted or knocked out DCAF15, that molecule was just as

1379
01:24:07.936 --> 01:24:11.736
potent. Clearly establishing that DCAF15 is not the functionally

1380
01:24:11.796 --> 01:24:12.696
required ligase.

1381
01:24:14.636 --> 01:24:17.396
To identify the ligase that is involved, we set up a CRISPR screen,

1382
01:24:18.196 --> 01:24:21.636
knocking out every E3 ligase encoded in the human genome and asking the question,

1383
01:24:22.016 --> 01:24:25.516
knockout of which ligase prevents IBG-1 from inducing BET4

1384
01:24:25.556 --> 01:24:26.156
degradation.

1385
01:24:27.056 --> 01:24:30.596
And this led to the identification of another E3 ligase called

1386
01:24:30.656 --> 01:24:34.556
DCAF16. And despite the very similar nomenclature, I think you can

1387
01:24:34.616 --> 01:24:38.196
appreciate by looking at the structure of both proteins in yellow bounds to their

1388
01:24:38.206 --> 01:24:40.096
adaptor protein, DDB1, that those

1389
01:24:41.076 --> 01:24:42.396
are quite dissimilar.

1390
01:24:44.036 --> 01:24:47.936
So we went on to further characterize IBG-1 and made a couple of curious

1391
01:24:47.996 --> 01:24:49.456
observations. The first one,

1392
01:24:50.276 --> 01:24:54.036
maybe as expected, when we test binding affinity of this molecule to the

1393
01:24:54.096 --> 01:24:58.016
E3 ligase, we did realize that indeed that molecule potently binds to

1394
01:24:58.036 --> 01:25:01.376
DCAF15, notably the ligase that functionally is not required.

1395
01:25:02.216 --> 01:25:06.076
Simultaneously, we could not detect any measurable binding to DCAF16, the ligase

1396
01:25:06.096 --> 01:25:07.436
that we have established as functionally

1397
01:25:07.476 --> 01:25:11.336
relevant.So what you need to know is that

1398
01:25:11.526 --> 01:25:14.226
RAD4 has two bromodomains at its N-terminus.

1399
01:25:14.586 --> 01:25:17.686
And typically, for any given PROTAC, it's sufficient to just have one of those

1400
01:25:17.706 --> 01:25:21.686
bromodomains fuse it to luciferase or to GFP, and the PROTAC

1401
01:25:21.786 --> 01:25:25.686
can degrade this fusion protein. However, with this molecule, IBG-1, it

1402
01:25:25.726 --> 01:25:28.826
was quite different because we needed both of the N-terminal bromodomains to be

1403
01:25:28.866 --> 01:25:30.166
accessible by the molecule.

1404
01:25:31.646 --> 01:25:35.486
And so these and other observations really only materialized when we

1405
01:25:35.546 --> 01:25:39.486
solved the cryo-EM structure of this ternary assembly and

1406
01:25:39.546 --> 01:25:43.186
found that counterintuitively, IBG-1 is not acting in trans,

1407
01:25:43.486 --> 01:25:47.316
binding the ligase and the target, but it acts in cis and it bridges these

1408
01:25:47.366 --> 01:25:51.286
two N-terminal bromodomains of RAD4, and this is then

1409
01:25:51.306 --> 01:25:54.676
sufficient to nucleate an interaction with DCAP16,

1410
01:25:55.126 --> 01:25:58.806
basically stabilizing a preexisting latent and weak interaction.

1411
01:25:59.986 --> 01:26:02.286
So we termed this intermolecular bivalent gluing.

1412
01:26:02.726 --> 01:26:06.066
We could show that this is extendable to other E3 ligases,

1413
01:26:06.766 --> 01:26:08.046
such as DCAP11.

1414
01:26:09.006 --> 01:26:11.726
And, we could structurally optimize these compounds.

1415
01:26:11.766 --> 01:26:15.306
And given that there is a large fraction of proteins in the human proteome that

1416
01:26:15.326 --> 01:26:19.226
have more than one domain, we think this is also potentially

1417
01:26:19.506 --> 01:26:20.316
widely applicable.

1418
01:26:23.106 --> 01:26:25.026
The last vignette I want to share with you

1419
01:26:26.326 --> 01:26:28.246
leads us a little bit away and

1420
01:26:29.106 --> 01:26:32.926
kind of starts with this observation that there are these episodic reports

1421
01:26:32.966 --> 01:26:36.406
of small molecules that were identified or developed as

1422
01:26:36.466 --> 01:26:40.166
inhibitors but still induced the degradation of their target proteins.

1423
01:26:40.196 --> 01:26:44.106
And this has been reported, for instance, for certain gene control factors

1424
01:26:44.146 --> 01:26:47.756
such as BCL6, lamin, or the estrogen receptor, but it's

1425
01:26:47.766 --> 01:26:50.646
particularly prevalent also for kinase and kinase inhibitors.

1426
01:26:51.646 --> 01:26:55.166
And so Natalie Schols, another former postdoc in my lab who

1427
01:26:55.646 --> 01:26:59.226
started this year her independent lab at the NKI in Amsterdam, was

1428
01:26:59.286 --> 01:27:03.266
interested in this phenomenon but wanted to approach it really from a systems-level

1429
01:27:03.346 --> 01:27:07.306
perspective, wanted to understand how frequently these events occur,

1430
01:27:08.166 --> 01:27:11.846
whether proximity induction is the underlying mechanistic principle, or whether

1431
01:27:11.946 --> 01:27:14.486
other mechanistic principles are at play.

1432
01:27:16.546 --> 01:27:19.805
So in order to systematically address that, she did a lot of work.

1433
01:27:20.206 --> 01:27:23.966
She made 100 different cell lines, each expressing a different kinase with a

1434
01:27:23.986 --> 01:27:27.526
luciferase fusion, and then exposed these 100 different cell lines against a

1435
01:27:27.586 --> 01:27:31.186
library of 1,500 kinase inhibitors, each in

1436
01:27:31.686 --> 01:27:35.366
time-ranging measurements. So she created overall more than

1437
01:27:35.506 --> 01:27:39.446
1.2 million protein stability measurements but did identify

1438
01:27:39.586 --> 01:27:43.466
450 new cases of inhibitor-induced target destabilization.

1439
01:27:44.566 --> 01:27:47.226
And so we looked into detail with some of them.

1440
01:27:47.486 --> 01:27:50.946
And I think what was very curious for see that in neither of those cases, we really

1441
01:27:50.956 --> 01:27:54.946
saw a traditional proximity induction where the kinase would be

1442
01:27:54.986 --> 01:27:58.066
paired with an E3 ligase that it typically doesn't meet.

1443
01:27:58.746 --> 01:28:02.586
Rather, what we see that these inhibitors lock a kinase in a state that

1444
01:28:02.626 --> 01:28:06.586
is more prone to be turned over by its native ligase, which just make these kinases

1445
01:28:06.646 --> 01:28:10.346
a bit more visible to their native degradation systems and we call this hence

1446
01:28:10.686 --> 01:28:13.086
supercharging of native degradation systems.

1447
01:28:13.126 --> 01:28:16.906
And mechanistically, we saw this can play out with different

1448
01:28:16.946 --> 01:28:20.486
mechanisms. So this can be ligand-induced oligomerization of

1449
01:28:20.506 --> 01:28:23.946
kinases, ligand-induced changes in localization of the kinase or also

1450
01:28:24.006 --> 01:28:24.846
activity state.

1451
01:28:25.706 --> 01:28:27.806
And so this was published late last year.

1452
01:28:28.606 --> 01:28:31.786
And early this year in a collaboration with Herbert Waldmann and Brenda Schulman

1453
01:28:31.806 --> 01:28:32.026
lab,

1454
01:28:32.926 --> 01:28:36.696
we could also expand the concept of inhibitor-induced supercharging outside of the

1455
01:28:36.766 --> 01:28:38.715
kinase or outside of the kinome,

1456
01:28:39.706 --> 01:28:43.426
as we report a new class of inhibitors for

1457
01:28:43.646 --> 01:28:47.286
IDO1, an immuno-oncology target that also induced the degradation of

1458
01:28:47.346 --> 01:28:51.076
IDO1. We found that this occurs via cofactor displacement and then

1459
01:28:51.106 --> 01:28:54.506
IDO1 adopts an APOL-like state that is then

1460
01:28:54.566 --> 01:28:55.126
more

1461
01:28:55.926 --> 01:28:59.666
effectively cleared by its native E3 ligase, KLHDC3,

1462
01:28:59.846 --> 01:29:01.826
that we also identified in this study.

1463
01:29:04.206 --> 01:29:08.186
So in conclusion, what I wanted to communicate with these last couple of

1464
01:29:08.226 --> 01:29:11.966
slides is that really our repertoire, our understanding and the repertoire of

1465
01:29:12.006 --> 01:29:14.886
targeted protein degradation is gradually increasing.

1466
01:29:15.586 --> 01:29:19.266
We're, as a community, very hopeful that this will precipitate in new

1467
01:29:19.306 --> 01:29:20.746
medicines for patients.

1468
01:29:21.886 --> 01:29:24.726
And to lead in the next part of my talk, I also want to share with you that there

1469
01:29:24.786 --> 01:29:28.766
is this paradoxic example that we still have FDA-approved

1470
01:29:28.806 --> 01:29:32.766
degraders in the clinic without really understanding

1471
01:29:32.966 --> 01:29:33.566
how they work.

1472
01:29:35.626 --> 01:29:39.446
And so this leads me to the second part where I want to

1473
01:29:39.526 --> 01:29:43.206
introduce a class of medicine that are called selective estrogen receptor degraders

1474
01:29:43.366 --> 01:29:47.326
or SERDs, which are cornerstone of the treatment of

1475
01:29:47.386 --> 01:29:51.206
ER-positive breast cancer patients, particularly relapsing and

1476
01:29:51.226 --> 01:29:54.866
metastatic patients. And the most well-known

1477
01:29:54.926 --> 01:29:57.486
SERD is a small molecule called fulvestrant.

1478
01:29:58.006 --> 01:29:59.806
It's clinically approved since 20 years.

1479
01:30:00.786 --> 01:30:04.686
And again, I think it's mind-blowing that really the way how fulvestrant

1480
01:30:04.726 --> 01:30:08.306
induces the degradation of the estrogen receptor has not been

1481
01:30:08.366 --> 01:30:09.366
understood in detail.

1482
01:30:11.126 --> 01:30:14.166
So this is something that we wanted to change, and this is a collaboration where we

1483
01:30:14.206 --> 01:30:16.926
teamed up with Nico Tomas lab at EPFL.

1484
01:30:17.486 --> 01:30:21.346
And for lack of time, I'm going to just share two large experiments that

1485
01:30:21.386 --> 01:30:25.126
we set up initially. One was, again, a CRISPR screen where we knock out

1486
01:30:25.286 --> 01:30:29.085
every gene in the human genome, asking knockout of which genes prevents SERDs from

1487
01:30:29.146 --> 01:30:31.666
inducing estrogen receptor degradation.

1488
01:30:31.686 --> 01:30:35.566
The second experiment was a proximity labeling coupled to proteomics, where we

1489
01:30:35.606 --> 01:30:39.386
can now ask the question, what are the interactors of the estrogen receptor when

1490
01:30:39.426 --> 01:30:42.446
it's liganded by fulvestrant or by other SERDs?

1491
01:30:44.426 --> 01:30:48.336
And so that allowed us to really map the entire pathway that is required for SERDs

1492
01:30:48.366 --> 01:30:50.236
in inducing estrogen receptor degradation.

1493
01:30:50.436 --> 01:30:54.346
It really shed light on another post-translational modification that is called

1494
01:30:54.386 --> 01:30:58.056
SUMOylation, which is a ubiquitin-like modification, and just as

1495
01:30:58.086 --> 01:31:02.006
ubiquitin is set on a target protein via a cascade of an SUMO E1,

1496
01:31:02.286 --> 01:31:05.886
E2, and E3. And we indeed mapped that entire pathway,

1497
01:31:05.906 --> 01:31:09.346
including several members of the PIAS family of SUMO E3

1498
01:31:09.406 --> 01:31:12.986
ligases. And so the SUMO-related estrogen receptors

1499
01:31:13.026 --> 01:31:16.526
then recognized and turned over by two fully

1500
01:31:16.606 --> 01:31:19.726
redundant ubiquitin ligases, RNF4 and

1501
01:31:19.866 --> 01:31:23.466
RNF111.So we were then surprised, right?

1502
01:31:23.546 --> 01:31:27.316
Typically, all the molecular degraders that I've told you about so far,

1503
01:31:27.566 --> 01:31:29.616
they basically functionalize this step here.

1504
01:31:29.826 --> 01:31:32.306
They reprogram an E3 ubiquitin ligase.

1505
01:31:32.366 --> 01:31:36.046
However, when we biochemically reconstituted this system, we

1506
01:31:36.066 --> 01:31:39.486
learned that the biochemical or the direct biochemical

1507
01:31:39.526 --> 01:31:42.046
activity of SERDs is actually to induce SUMOylation.

1508
01:31:42.466 --> 01:31:45.706
So they don't rewire an E3 ubiquitin ligase, they act as

1509
01:31:45.726 --> 01:31:47.946
SUMO-inducing a small molecule drugs.

1510
01:31:49.966 --> 01:31:53.926
So now having met the degradation pathway for the first time, we could also ask

1511
01:31:53.966 --> 01:31:57.446
the question, how relevant is the degradation of the estrogen receptor actually for

1512
01:31:57.506 --> 01:32:01.106
the efficacy of these medicines? And so we started by

1513
01:32:01.126 --> 01:32:04.686
performing a xenograft study, either using cell lines that are

1514
01:32:04.706 --> 01:32:08.106
proficient for RNF4 and RNF111, or in

1515
01:32:08.146 --> 01:32:11.626
cells using cells where both of these E3 ligases have been knocked out.

1516
01:32:12.506 --> 01:32:16.226
And again, to our surprise, we realized that fulvestrant doesn't really care.

1517
01:32:16.266 --> 01:32:20.126
If we deprive it of its activity of inducing ER degradation,

1518
01:32:20.346 --> 01:32:21.856
those molecules are just as active.

1519
01:32:22.496 --> 01:32:25.626
We could validate the same finding with transcriptional reporters.

1520
01:32:26.326 --> 01:32:29.886
So what you see here is basically a gene set of the estrogen receptor.

1521
01:32:29.946 --> 01:32:33.726
If the bar goes down, that means the drug is inhibiting ER transcription.

1522
01:32:34.086 --> 01:32:36.266
If we test this with a PROTAC, you see it go down.

1523
01:32:36.606 --> 01:32:40.566
If we knock out the relevant ligase, in this case, cereblon, the PROTAC loses this

1524
01:32:40.626 --> 01:32:44.486
activity. Looks very different with the SERDs, where you see a

1525
01:32:44.566 --> 01:32:46.626
very strong anti-estrogenic response.

1526
01:32:46.686 --> 01:32:49.446
If we knock out these two ligases, this is not impaired.

1527
01:32:50.636 --> 01:32:52.126
And so if we then moved to longer

1528
01:32:52.966 --> 01:32:56.606
proliferation studies that allow us more granular control over the concentrations

1529
01:32:56.646 --> 01:32:59.986
that we test compared to the in vivo experiment, we found actually something that

1530
01:33:00.026 --> 01:33:03.866
was particularly curious for us. We found exactly the opposite of what we would

1531
01:33:03.906 --> 01:33:07.446
have expected. So when we stabilize the estrogen receptor by

1532
01:33:07.506 --> 01:33:11.266
removing both of those ligases, SERDs don't lose their activity, they

1533
01:33:11.326 --> 01:33:14.986
actually get more potent. Insinuating that they really require

1534
01:33:15.026 --> 01:33:18.836
estrogen receptor to unlock their full potency and that there

1535
01:33:18.886 --> 01:33:22.366
is some sort of dominant repressive pharmacology at play.

1536
01:33:24.586 --> 01:33:27.766
So having established that degradation is functionally inconsequential for SERDs,

1537
01:33:27.806 --> 01:33:30.625
we naturally ask the question, what are the effectors that are driving its

1538
01:33:30.685 --> 01:33:33.366
efficacy and performed another genome wide screen.

1539
01:33:33.486 --> 01:33:36.946
Here now looking at viability or cellular fitness as a readout.

1540
01:33:37.806 --> 01:33:41.436
So we knock out every gene and ask the question, knock out of which gene prevents

1541
01:33:41.436 --> 01:33:45.006
the activity or this anti-cytostatic effect of the SERDs.

1542
01:33:45.046 --> 01:33:48.766
And, again, interestingly, we find core

1543
01:33:48.806 --> 01:33:52.666
members of the SUMOylation machinery, letting us conclude

1544
01:33:52.676 --> 01:33:56.206
that full SERD efficacy really requires active SUMOylation.

1545
01:33:57.506 --> 01:34:00.255
Again, this is something that we could also validate when looking at

1546
01:34:00.286 --> 01:34:04.226
transcriptional profiling. So again, this is a gene set enrichment analysis,

1547
01:34:04.546 --> 01:34:07.206
and you see that fulvestrant has these very strong,

1548
01:34:08.066 --> 01:34:10.996
antagonistic properties on ER transcription.

1549
01:34:11.346 --> 01:34:15.286
However, if we block cells with a pharmacological inhibitor of the SUMOylation

1550
01:34:15.346 --> 01:34:19.316
cascade, we completely revert that phenotype, meaning that,

1551
01:34:19.426 --> 01:34:23.346
again, SUMOylation is required for the full ER antagonism elicited

1552
01:34:23.426 --> 01:34:23.906
by SERDs.

1553
01:34:25.806 --> 01:34:29.496
Mechanistically, we could found that when the estrogen receptor is

1554
01:34:29.566 --> 01:34:33.146
decorated with these SUMO chains, it's also bound by a network of different

1555
01:34:33.156 --> 01:34:37.106
transcriptional repressors, particularly the NURD complex, that keeps this

1556
01:34:37.146 --> 01:34:40.926
in a transcriptionally fully inert state, immobilized on chromatin.

1557
01:34:41.176 --> 01:34:45.106
This immobilization is also something that colleagues at Genentech have shown a

1558
01:34:45.146 --> 01:34:46.946
couple of years ago.

1559
01:34:48.146 --> 01:34:52.026
So in sum, what I've shared with you, and this is still unpublished work

1560
01:34:52.446 --> 01:34:56.226
about our studies of the mechanism of action of SERDs, is that fulvestrant

1561
01:34:56.266 --> 01:34:59.746
binds to the estrogen receptor and directly induces ER SUMOylation.

1562
01:35:00.166 --> 01:35:03.906
Then the SUMOylated ER is ubiquitinated and degraded by the

1563
01:35:03.946 --> 01:35:07.606
redundant action of these two E3 ligases, called RNF4 and

1564
01:35:07.686 --> 01:35:10.966
RNF11. However, ER degradation is

1565
01:35:11.026 --> 01:35:14.926
inconsequential or in some stages or in some settings, even detrimental

1566
01:35:14.966 --> 01:35:17.695
for the transcriptional disruption cytostatic activity of SERDs.

1567
01:35:18.426 --> 01:35:21.506
In contrast, we found that SUMOylation is causative for the full transcriptional

1568
01:35:21.566 --> 01:35:24.116
disruption, and the cellular efficacy of SERDs.

1569
01:35:24.146 --> 01:35:28.086
And mechanistically, we believe that the SUMOylated ER is really bound

1570
01:35:28.126 --> 01:35:31.766
by transcriptional repressors immobilized on chromatin and acting as

1571
01:35:32.266 --> 01:35:34.146
a dominant repressive signal.

1572
01:35:35.266 --> 01:35:35.456
And

1573
01:35:37.026 --> 01:35:40.665
importantly to state, fulvestrant is not the only drug that induces

1574
01:35:40.766 --> 01:35:44.706
SUMOylation of its target and then some sort of immobilization on chromatin.

1575
01:35:44.806 --> 01:35:45.126
In fact,

1576
01:35:46.206 --> 01:35:49.726
once we got into this space, you then realize that there is actually a number of

1577
01:35:49.866 --> 01:35:53.766
FDA-approved drugs or agents that are in clinical investigation that do

1578
01:35:53.786 --> 01:35:57.646
exactly the same. Mechanistically, via different pathways or different

1579
01:35:57.686 --> 01:36:01.026
principles. But in the end, they lead to immobilization and

1580
01:36:01.066 --> 01:36:02.986
SUMOylation of the targets on chromatin.

1581
01:36:03.826 --> 01:36:07.806
And so also given that there's a lot of evidence emerging in the field and

1582
01:36:08.026 --> 01:36:11.806
Lacra Pinto's lab in Stanford is leading that space, that SUMOylation is

1583
01:36:11.886 --> 01:36:14.506
also really a central cue in transcriptional repression.

1584
01:36:14.826 --> 01:36:18.726
We really believe that this is maybe one of those cases, just as targeted protein

1585
01:36:18.766 --> 01:36:22.706
degradation a decade ago, where we have a clinical validation of a modality

1586
01:36:22.746 --> 01:36:24.886
that was never purposefully developed that way.

1587
01:36:25.666 --> 01:36:29.326
And that it could be a strategy to purposefully shut down

1588
01:36:29.366 --> 01:36:30.646
oncogenic transcription.

1589
01:36:33.246 --> 01:36:36.706
Okay, so for the last couple of minutes, I want to go back to the beginning, where

1590
01:36:36.726 --> 01:36:40.386
I've told you that small molecule degraders are chemical neomorphs

1591
01:36:40.486 --> 01:36:44.366
that rewire an E3 ubiquitin ligase to, in the end,

1592
01:36:44.966 --> 01:36:47.966
elicit a very potent loss of function on the target protein.

1593
01:36:48.006 --> 01:36:51.626
So we rewire an effector to eliminate a target.

1594
01:36:52.706 --> 01:36:56.646
And I think from a conceptual perspective, it's also interesting to

1595
01:36:56.706 --> 01:37:00.426
review that really we've, as a community, put a lot of effort

1596
01:37:00.786 --> 01:37:02.696
on these loss of function therapies, right?

1597
01:37:02.946 --> 01:37:06.436
Maybe with exception of CAR T-cells or T-cell engagers, and I'm sure there are many

1598
01:37:06.526 --> 01:37:10.006
other exceptions, but I think in the field of small molecule discovery, it's fair

1599
01:37:10.026 --> 01:37:13.786
to say that frequently we're looking for one particular wire, want to

1600
01:37:13.826 --> 01:37:17.626
cut it, and then hope that in this very complex wiring of cancer cells, that this

1601
01:37:17.686 --> 01:37:19.745
is sufficient to induce cell death.

1602
01:37:20.866 --> 01:37:24.346
And so over the last couple of slides, I want to share with you what could we do

1603
01:37:24.406 --> 01:37:28.286
if, instead of rewiring an effector to eliminate the target, we

1604
01:37:28.326 --> 01:37:30.026
could just directly rewire the

1605
01:37:30.086 --> 01:37:33.876
target.Again, as everything, this is

1606
01:37:33.896 --> 01:37:36.936
motivated by work that others have been doing before.

1607
01:37:36.966 --> 01:37:38.895
And there's two studies I want to highlight.

1608
01:37:39.536 --> 01:37:43.476
One earlier study from the Bradner and Sari lab, where they could show

1609
01:37:43.516 --> 01:37:47.456
that you can recruit BD4 to repressive and repetitive regions in the

1610
01:37:47.476 --> 01:37:51.106
chromatin, and this is then sufficient to nucleate a transcriptional

1611
01:37:51.106 --> 01:37:54.916
response. And then, a more recent study by Nathaniel Gray and Chirag

1612
01:37:55.036 --> 01:37:58.956
Kheradchi where they could show that you can also recruit BD4, but also other

1613
01:37:58.996 --> 01:38:02.956
transcriptional co-activators to BCL6 and thereby actively

1614
01:38:03.876 --> 01:38:07.176
flipping a switch and turning this repressor into an activator.

1615
01:38:07.856 --> 01:38:10.316
And we felt that this is incredibly exciting field.

1616
01:38:10.956 --> 01:38:14.596
And so we wanted to basically ask the question whether we can also

1617
01:38:14.676 --> 01:38:16.776
reprogram chromatin remodeling complexes.

1618
01:38:17.256 --> 01:38:20.736
So again, we focus here on BCL6. BCL6 is a

1619
01:38:20.756 --> 01:38:24.496
transcriptional repressor. This is a target in lymphomas that sits on

1620
01:38:24.536 --> 01:38:28.256
chromatin and represses the activity of different genes, particularly

1621
01:38:28.336 --> 01:38:31.756
also proapoptotic genes. So our therapeutic

1622
01:38:31.776 --> 01:38:35.595
hypothesis was that maybe we can recruit the BAF complex to

1623
01:38:35.816 --> 01:38:39.476
change chromatin conformation around BCL6 binding sites and to

1624
01:38:39.516 --> 01:38:43.376
establish a chromatin state that is more permissive for transcriptional activity.

1625
01:38:44.176 --> 01:38:45.896
Many of you will be aware of the BAF complex.

1626
01:38:45.956 --> 01:38:48.336
It's mutated in 20% of all human cancer.

1627
01:38:48.656 --> 01:38:50.716
But in this case, again, let me rephrase.

1628
01:38:50.796 --> 01:38:52.756
We are not trying to inhibit the BAF complex.

1629
01:38:52.796 --> 01:38:56.376
We just try to borrow it to effectively rewire

1630
01:38:56.556 --> 01:38:57.776
BCL6 as a target.

1631
01:38:59.676 --> 01:39:03.516
So together with Christian Steinebach, we developed bifunctional

1632
01:39:03.576 --> 01:39:07.536
molecules that on the one hand binds to the BTB domain of BCL6, and on the

1633
01:39:07.576 --> 01:39:11.116
other hand bind to the bromodomain of SMARCA2/4 which are the

1634
01:39:11.136 --> 01:39:14.136
catalytic active subunits of the BAF complex.

1635
01:39:15.276 --> 01:39:18.456
So again, in in vitro experiments, we could show that we can effectively induce

1636
01:39:18.476 --> 01:39:21.236
proximity between BCL6 and SMARCA2/4.

1637
01:39:23.016 --> 01:39:26.496
And we could also immobilize this bromodomain ligand

1638
01:39:27.016 --> 01:39:30.496
and perform chemoproteomics. And that allowed us really to basically pull

1639
01:39:30.556 --> 01:39:34.256
down the entire BAF complex, letting us conclude that with

1640
01:39:34.316 --> 01:39:37.596
liganding this bromodomain, we really have chemical control and chemical

1641
01:39:37.636 --> 01:39:41.236
accessibility of the entire BAF complex.

1642
01:39:43.036 --> 01:39:45.436
We then set up a cellular target engagement assay,

1643
01:39:46.376 --> 01:39:50.306
that basically tells us that at the concentration of around a micromolar, we only

1644
01:39:50.316 --> 01:39:54.076
engage between 5 or 10% of the BAF complex that is

1645
01:39:54.116 --> 01:39:57.156
expressed in a given lymphoma cell line.

1646
01:39:57.196 --> 01:39:59.376
And then we performed cut and run experiments.

1647
01:39:59.386 --> 01:40:02.776
So this is similar to Chip-seq, where we can track abundance or

1648
01:40:02.936 --> 01:40:05.856
positioning of different factors on a chromatin-wide scale.

1649
01:40:06.456 --> 01:40:09.396
Here we focus on known BCL6 target sites.

1650
01:40:09.436 --> 01:40:13.296
And what these graphs tell us is that indeed we can see a recruitment

1651
01:40:13.356 --> 01:40:16.756
of the BAF complex. Here, cut and run data showing for

1652
01:40:16.916 --> 01:40:20.696
SMARCA4 that this goes hand-in-hand with an eviction of

1653
01:40:20.736 --> 01:40:24.136
BCL6 at those sites and then an establishment of

1654
01:40:24.636 --> 01:40:27.976
transcriptionally active and permissive chromatin states.

1655
01:40:29.576 --> 01:40:33.476
The functional consequence of this is a transcriptional induction of BCL6

1656
01:40:33.516 --> 01:40:37.136
target genes that are specific for this molecule that we termed

1657
01:40:37.436 --> 01:40:37.916
TRIP1,

1658
01:40:38.896 --> 01:40:42.756
and also important induction of apoptotic cell

1659
01:40:42.816 --> 01:40:46.676
death. Which again, was specific for these neomorphic molecules and

1660
01:40:46.716 --> 01:40:50.496
something that we could not achieve with either BTB domain inhibition or also

1661
01:40:50.566 --> 01:40:52.176
degradation of BCL6.

1662
01:40:54.556 --> 01:40:57.976
So with that, I want to conclude. I hope I could convince you that targeted protein

1663
01:40:57.996 --> 01:41:01.776
degradation is really a powerful loss of function modality that is based on

1664
01:41:01.816 --> 01:41:03.896
reprogramming or rewiring E3 ligases.

1665
01:41:04.756 --> 01:41:08.236
I think we're hopeful as a community that it will allow us to continue to

1666
01:41:08.276 --> 01:41:11.436
expand the tractable target space in the human proteome.

1667
01:41:11.636 --> 01:41:14.936
And I think it will benefit from really rational strategies for molecular glue

1668
01:41:14.976 --> 01:41:17.045
discovery and design moving forward.

1669
01:41:18.096 --> 01:41:21.616
As a community, I think we should also think beyond loss of function

1670
01:41:21.676 --> 01:41:24.396
approaches. At least I'm incredibly excited about it.

1671
01:41:24.436 --> 01:41:27.636
And there was also a brilliant induced proximity lecture

1672
01:41:27.916 --> 01:41:31.636
yesterday chaired by Michael Erb, and I think there's a lot of momentum in that

1673
01:41:31.676 --> 01:41:32.036
space.

1674
01:41:32.876 --> 01:41:36.256
I've shared with you vignettes that speak to how we can rewire

1675
01:41:36.316 --> 01:41:40.036
sumoylation networks to induce repressive

1676
01:41:40.045 --> 01:41:43.216
dominant signal, which could go beyond loss of function.

1677
01:41:43.256 --> 01:41:47.076
And on the other hand, I've shared with you data of how we can directly rewire

1678
01:41:47.416 --> 01:41:50.676
repressive targets by recruiting the BAF complex.

1679
01:41:50.705 --> 01:41:54.256
And I think really the rate-limiting step in the field here is our

1680
01:41:54.296 --> 01:41:58.176
imagination and our creativity. And there's obviously many more biological

1681
01:41:58.196 --> 01:42:02.016
processes that can be reprogrammed and rewired with small molecules.

1682
